{"title_page": "Haim (band)", "text_new": "{{short description|American pop rock band}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Haim\n| background       = group_or_band\n| image            = Haim Way Out West 2013.jpg\n| landscape        = yes\n| caption          = Haim performing at the [[Way Out West (festival)|Way Out West]] festival in [[Gothenburg]], Sweden, in 2013.<br/>From left: Alana, Danielle, Este Haim\n| alias            = \n| origin           = [[San Fernando Valley]], [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| genre            = <!-- Only seperate with commas per [[Template:Infobox musical artist]]. -->{{hlist|[[Rock music|Rock]]|[[soft rock]]|[[pop rock]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]}} <!-- DO NOT CHANGE GENRE WITHOUT SEEKING DISCUSSION AND ACHIEVING CONSENSUS ON THE ARTICLE TALK PAGE.  -->\n| years_active     = {{Start date|2007}}\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|[[Roc Nation]]|[[Polydor Records|Polydor]]|[[Columbia Records|Columbia]]}}\n| associated_acts  =\n| website          = {{URL|haimtheband.com}}\n| current_members  = * Este Haim\n* Danielle Haim\n* Alana Haim\n}}\n\n'''Haim''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|h|a\u026a|\u026a|m}} {{respell|HY|im}},<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JW2HaLoxPTw |title=Pronunciation Guide: HAIM Teach You How To Say Their Name |via=[[YouTube]] |date=November 21, 2013 |accessdate=July 30, 2014}}</ref>{{efn|According to the band, an English approximation of the original Hebrew, meaning \"life\", can be \"high-im\"<ref name=\"lamont\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/sep/22/haim-sisters-days-gone-interview|title=Haim: 'Dad would be like, Let's go and jam in the living room|first=Tom|last=Lamont|newspaper=The Observer|date=September 22, 2013|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref>}} stylized in [[all caps]]) is an American [[pop rock]] band from Los Angeles. The band consists of three sisters: Este Haim (bass guitar and vocals), Danielle Haim (vocals and guitar) and Alana Haim (guitars, keyboards, and vocals). In addition to their primary instruments, each member is also proficient in several others. The group's pop sound on their studio work stands in contrast to the more rock-based music of their live shows.\n\nThe sisters grew up in a musical family, and began playing instruments from an early age in the [[cover band]] Rockinhaim, fronted by their parents, [[Mordechai Haim|Moti]] and Donna. The two elder sisters, Este and Danielle, began performing with the pop group Valli Girls in 2005. They released a few songs on soundtrack and compilation albums under that name, but left the group shortly after an appearance at the 2005 [[Nickelodeon Kids' Choice Awards]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thefader.com/2013/06/25/haim-best-friends-forever|title=Haim: Best Friends Forever|work=The FADER|access-date=October 19, 2017|language=en}}</ref> They formed Haim with younger sister Alana in 2007, but did not seriously consider it a professional career for some years. After Danielle became a successful touring guitarist, first with [[Jenny Lewis]] and later with [[Julian Casablancas]], Haim reformed as a full-time operation in 2012.\n\nThe group's first release, ''Forever'' (an EP released as a limited-time download), combined with positive reception at the [[South by Southwest]] festival, led to a deal with [[Polydor Records]] and a management deal with [[Jay-Z]]'s [[Roc Nation]] group in mid-2012. The band began recording material for their first album, ''[[Days Are Gone]]'', in sessions between touring dates, including appearances at the [[Glastonbury Festival]]. The album charted in the top ten in several countries, including the number-one spot in the UK, and the group had won several \"best of\" awards by the end of 2013. The group was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]] at the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards]]. Their second album, ''[[Something to Tell You]]'', was released in July 2017.<ref name=nyt>{{cite news |last=Reznick |first=Melissa |date=July 6, 2017 |title= Haim Wants to Prove That Vintage Vibes Feel Just Fine Now|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/06/arts/music/haim-something-to-tell-you-interview.html |work=New York Times |location= New York|access-date=July 6, 2017}}</ref>  Their forthcoming third album, titled ''[[Women in Music Pt. III]]'', is scheduled for release on August 21, 2020.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early career===\n[[File:Danielle Haim Way Out West 2013 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Danielle Haim at [[Way Out West (festival)|Way Out West]] 2013 in [[Gothenburg, Sweden]]]]\nThe three sisters, '''Este Arielle Haim''' (born March 14, 1986), '''Danielle Sari Haim''' (born February 16, 1989) and '''Alana Mychal Haim''' (born December 15, 1991) were all born and raised in the [[San Fernando Valley]], [[California]], and are [[Jewish]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejc.com/news/world-news/96586/jewish-singers-haim-tipped-sound-2013|title=Jewish singers Haim tipped as Sound of 2013|newspaper=The Jewish Chronicle}}</ref>  Their [[Israeli people|Israeli]]-born father [[Mordechai Haim|Mordechai]] (\"Moti\") and their mother Donna were both musical; though he had been a professional soccer player in Israel, Moti also played drums, while Donna won a contest on ''[[The Gong Show]]'' in the 1970s singing a [[Bonnie Raitt]] song.<ref name=\"salon\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.spin.com/featured/haim-spin-2013-october-cover-story|title=Falling for Haim|magazine=Spin|first=Camille|last=Dodero|date=September 30, 2013|accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Vogue\"/><ref name=\"lester\"/> While Danielle showed an aptitude for the guitar at a young age, Moti made the decision that Este would be more suited to the bass, buying her a second hand [[Fender bass|Fender]] for $50.<ref name=\"weiner\"/> The siblings were encouraged to listen to their parents' 1970s [[classic rock]] and [[Americana (music)|Americana]] records and, during their childhood, the family formed a band called Rockinhaim to play cover versions at local charity fairs, with Moti on drums and Donna on guitar.<ref name=\"Vogue\" /><ref name=\"Guardian20121124\" /><ref name=\"Interview\">{{cite web |first=Emma |last=Brown |title=Discovery: HAIM |work=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]] |url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/music/discovery-haim |accessdate= December 12, 2012}}</ref> The group played typical wedding band material, including [[the Beatles]]' \"[[Get Back]]\", [[Billy Joel]]'s \"[[You May Be Right (song)|You May Be Right]]\" and [[Van Morrison]]'s \"[[Brown Eyed Girl]]\",<ref name=\"Evening Standard\"/> but only did free community and benefit gigs at churches, schools and hospitals.<ref name=\"salon\"/>\n\nDanielle and Este were members of the pop-rock group the Valli Girls, and appeared on the soundtrack to the 2005 film ''[[The Sisterhood of the Traveling Pants (film)|The Sisterhood of the Traveling Pants]]''.<ref name=\"weiner\"/> Their song \"Valli Nation\" by the \"SoCal teen prodigies\" appeared on the 2005 [[Nickelodeon Kids' Choice Awards]] soundtrack alongside established musicians [[Avril Lavigne]], [[Alicia Keys]], [[Simple Plan]] and [[Good Charlotte]].<ref name=\"PRnewswire\">{{cite news |title=So-Cal Teen Prodigies The Valli Girls Launch Pop-Rock Campaign |publisher=[[Columbia Records]] |location=New York City |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/so-cal-teen-prodigies-the-valli-girls-launch-pop-rock-campaign-54307652.html |date=April 14, 2005 |accessdate=January 11, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130815021942/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/so-cal-teen-prodigies-the-valli-girls-launch-pop-rock-campaign-54307652.html |archive-date=August 15, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Este Haim Way Out West 2013 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Este Haim at Way Out West 2013 in Gothenburg, Sweden]]\nAs they grew older, the sisters became more interested in incorporating pop and [[contemporary R&B]] into their music, and in 2007 they decided to form their own band.<ref name=\"weiner\">{{cite journal|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/how-haims-three-geeky-sisters-became-the-years-coolest-new-band-20131112|title=How Haim's Three Geeky Sisters Became the Year's Coolest New Band|first=Jonah|last=Weiner|journal=Rolling Stone|date=November 12, 2013|accessdate=October 20, 2014}}</ref> For their first gig, the trio played at a Jewish deli in Hollywood and were paid in [[matzah ball soup]].<ref name=\"Independent\">{{cite news |first=Barry |last=Egan |title=Music: Haim \u2013 Sisters of super sounds |newspaper=The Independent|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/music/music-haim-sisters-of-super-sounds-29739021.html |date=November 10, 2013 |accessdate=May 19, 2014}}</ref> Early gigs were sparsely populated; Danielle recalled, \"We were [at the] bottom of the bill at 50-capacity venues and no one would show up.\"<ref name=\"mccormick\"/>\n\nFor the next five years, Haim played local venues but did not consider music as a professional career, because all three sisters were busy with other projects. Este was studying at [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]] and graduated in 2010 with a degree in Ethnomusicology (completed in just two years instead of the normal five),<ref name=\"Guardian20121124\" /><ref name=\"Evening Standard\">{{cite news |first=David |last=Smyth |title=Soundcheck: Haim |newspaper=[[Evening Standard]] |location=London, England |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/arts/music/soundcheck-haim-7682181.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130505044758/http://www.standard.co.uk/arts/music/soundcheck-haim-7682181.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=May 5, 2013 |date=April 27, 2012 |accessdate=January 9, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"Shalom\" /> specializing in Bulgarian and Brazilian music.<ref name=\"Evening Standard\"/>\n\n===Danielle Haim's guest appearances===\nAfter graduating from high school, Danielle was spotted by musician [[Jenny Lewis]] at a jam session in [[Laurel Canyon]], which led to Danielle joining Lewis' touring band.<ref name=\"weiner\"/> [[The Strokes]]' singer [[Julian Casablancas]] came to see one of Lewis's shows on tour, and he in turn asked Danielle to play guitar and percussion on his solo tour.<ref name=\"Interview\" /> Danielle rehearsed with Casablancas' band every day for two months, which she later described as \"an eye-opening experience.\"<ref name=\"Evening Standard\"/> Following working with Casablancas from late 2009 to mid 2010, she auditioned for a place in [[Scarlet Fever (band)|Scarlet Fever]], the all-female backing band for [[CeeLo Green]]. Danielle performed only once with the group, on [[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://jennylsq.libsyn.com/danielle-haim-lisa-left-eye-lopes|title=Danielle Haim // Lisa \"Left-Eye\" Lopes|last=Eliscu|first=Jenny|date=May 23, 2018|work=LSQ|access-date=July 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWhile Danielle enjoyed touring, she decided she would prefer to perform her own music alongside her sisters,<ref name=\"Evening Standard\"/> turning down a lucrative tour deal with Green.<ref name=\"mccormick\"/> Casablancas advised Danielle to write stronger material and focus on recording, as it would improve their online presence.<ref name=\"weiner\"/>\n\n===2012\u201313: ''Forever'' and commercial success===\n[[File:Alana Haim Way Out West 2013 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Alana Haim at Way Out West 2013 in Gothenburg, Sweden]]\nAfter playing shows supporting [[Edward Sharpe and the Magnetic Zeros]], [[The Henry Clay People]] and [[Kesha]], Haim released the [[Extended play|EP]] ''Forever,'' which included three songs in February 2012 as a time-limited free download on their website. Dash Hutton officially joined as drummer at the EP's release party at the Los Angeles Bootleg Theatre.<ref name=\"salon\"/> He is the son of [[Three Dog Night]]'s [[Danny Hutton]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20122666,00.html|title=Rock on|work=people.com}}</ref> and knew Este socially after she had seen his old band, [[Wires on Fire]].<ref name=\"salon\"/><ref name=\"Shalom\">{{cite web|first=Ashley |last=Baylen |title=Exclusive Interview With the Girls of 'HAIM' |work=Shalom Life |url=http://www.shalomlife.com/culture/18222/exclusive-interview-with-the-girls-of-haim/ |date=November 7, 2012 |accessdate=December 12, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121130092519/http://www.shalomlife.com/culture/18222/exclusive-interview-with-the-girls-of-haim/ |archivedate=November 30, 2012 }}</ref> The EP received attention from the music industry following a successful series of shows at the [[South by Southwest]] festival in March.<ref>''Music Week'' staff. (June 1, 2012). \"The Playlist\", ''[[Music Week]]''. (22):6</ref> Danielle recalled the first show was \"maybe a disaster\", but the remainder of the shows attracted more attention.<ref name=\"Evening Standard\"/> The band subsequently signed a deal with [[Polydor Records]] in the UK in June.<ref>{{cite news |title=Polydor UK Signs Haim |url=http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/polydor-uk-signs-haim/049252 |newspaper=[[Music Week]] |location=London, England |date=June 19, 2012 |accessdate=December 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn July, independent record label National Anthem re-released the ''Forever'' EP on 10\" vinyl, containing the original three songs along with a fourth track, a remix of \"Forever\" by [[Dan Lissvik]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Cragg |title=New music: Haim \u2013 Forever |newspaper=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2012/jun/07/new-music-haim-forever |date=June 7, 2012 |accessdate=January 9, 2013}}</ref> Following dates supporting [[Mumford & Sons]] on their Gentlemen of the Road tour in the US in August,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/08/02/mumford-and-sons-babel-new-songs-music_n_1733617.html|title=Mumford & Sons And 'Babel': Band Performs New Songs At Hoboken Concert (VIDEO)|work=The Huffington post|date=August 2, 2012|accessdate=February 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The Maccabees, Gogol Bordello, Haim, St Vincent to play Mumford and Sons' US mini-festivals |newspaper=[[NME]]|location=London, England |url=http://www.nme.com/news/mumford-and-sons/64063 |date=May 30, 2012 |accessdate=December 12, 2012}}</ref> Haim toured the UK for the first time in November 2012<ref>{{cite news |title=Haim announce debut UK tour \u2013 ticket details |newspaper=NME |url=http://www.nme.com/news/haim/65803 |date=August 29, 2012 |accessdate=December 12, 2012}}</ref> and then supported [[Florence and the Machine]] on their UK and Ireland tour in December.<ref>{{cite web |title=Florence & The Machine confirm O2 Dublin 2012 live concert date for Wednesday December 12th! |url=http://musicscene.ie/2012/09/florence-the-machine-confirm-o2-dublin-2012-live-concert-date-for-wednesday-december-12th/ |work=Music Scene |date=September 10, 2012 |accessdate=December 12, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Ben |last=Homewood |title=Haim To Support Florence + The Machine |newspaper=[[The Fly (magazine)|The Fly]] |location=London, England |url=http://www.the-fly.co.uk/news/article/1015499/haim-to-support-florence-the-machine/ |date=September 13, 2012 |accessdate=December 12, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121028022457/http://www.the-fly.co.uk/news/article/1015499/haim-to-support-florence-the-machine/ |archive-date=October 28, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBritish music magazine ''[[New Musical Express]]'' made the title track of the ''Forever'' EP its number 4 track of 2012.<ref>{{cite news |title=Albums and Tracks of the Year for 2012 |newspaper=NME |url=http://www.nme.com/bestalbumsandtracksoftheyear/2012 |date=December 2, 2012 |accessdate=December 12, 2012}}</ref> On January 4, 2013, the [[BBC]] announced that Haim had topped their annual [[Sound of...|Sound of 2013]] music industry poll to find the most promising new musical acts for the coming year.<ref name=\"so13\">{{cite web |first=Ian |last=Youngs |title=Haim top BBC Sound of 2013 list |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-20900614 |date=January 4, 2013 |accessdate=January 9, 2013}}</ref> The group also signed a management contract with the conglomerate [[Roc Nation]], returned to South by SouthWest in March 2013<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-25419364|title=Haim: Sound of 2013 winners look back|first=Mark|last=Savage|work=BBC News|date=January 3, 2014|accessdate=February 11, 2014}}</ref> and earned their own \"At Your Request\" video feature on [[Idolator (website)|Idolator]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Adickman|first=Erika Brooks|title=HAIM's \"Don't Save Me\": At Your Request|url=http://idolator.com/7446604/haim-dont-save-me-at-your-request|work=Idolator|accessdate=March 14, 2013}}</ref> In early 2013, they were featured on American recording artist [[Kid Cudi]]'s third studio album ''[[Indicud]]'', on the song titled \"Red Eye\".<ref name=\"indicud\">{{cite news|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/03/kid-cudi-unveils-indicud-album-art-and-tracklist|title=Kid Cudi Unveils \"Indicud\" Album Art and Tracklist|last=Weiss|first=Sam|date=March 26, 2013|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|accessdate=March 27, 2013}}</ref> Danielle Haim appeared on the first track, \"You're No Good\", from [[Major Lazer]]'s second album, ''[[Free the Universe]]'', alongside [[Santigold]], [[Vybz Kartel]] and Yasmin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/free-the-universe-mw0002413340|title=Free The Universe|first=David|last=Jeffries|work=AllMusic|accessdate=October 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2013\u201314: ''Days Are Gone''===\n[[File:Danielle Haim performing.png|thumb|left|upright|Danielle Haim performing in [[Indio, California]], April 2014]]\nThe group spent a year recording their first album, ''[[Days Are Gone]]'', in sessions between live shows.<ref name=\"weiner\"/> The group experimented with [[drum machine]]s and the music program [[GarageBand]], adding [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] influences to their existing sound.<ref name=\"weiner\"/> Polydor recommended producers [[Ariel Rechtshaid]] and [[James Ford (musician)|James Ford]] to help with the album, who suggested further use of [[synthesizer]]s, bringing the album closer to a straightforward pop style.<ref name=\"nmedog\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/haim/14835|title=Haim \u2013 'Days Are Gone'|first=Hazel|last=Sheffield|journal=New Musical Express|date=September 30, 2013|accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref> Several of the drum tracks were recorded with [[gated reverb]], made famous by [[Phil Collins]].<ref name=\"petridis\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/sep/26/haim-days-are-gone-review|title=Haim: Days Are Gone \u2013 review|first=Alexis|last=Petridis|newspaper=The Guardian|date=September 26, 2013|accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref> In June 2013, the group performed at [[Glastonbury Festival]], and in addition to their own set, the band appeared with [[Primal Scream]] performing background vocals on \"It's Alright, It's OK\", \"Rocks\" and \"[[Come Together]]\".<ref name=\"lamont\"/>  The band later returned for a repeat performance at Glastonbury in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/events/errnc8/acts/azf4wh#p021sfd2|title=Glastonbury 2014 \u2013 Haim|work=BBC Music|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref> After their set, Este nearly had a [[diabetic]] seizure. She has [[Type 1 diabetes]] and was diagnosed with it in 2000.<ref>{{cite news|title=Este Haim discusses type 1 diabetes and performing at T in the Park 2014|url=http://www.diabetes.co.uk/news/2014/jul/este-haim-discusses-type-1-diabetes-and-performing-at-t-in-the-park-2014-90803920.html|accessdate=June 23, 2017|work=diabetes.co.uk|date=July 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Trendell|first1=Andrew|title=ESTE HAIM: 'I ALMOST DIED AT GLASTONBURY|url=http://www.gigwise.com/news/92895/este-haim-i-almost-died-from-diabetes-at-glastonbury|date=July 24, 2014|publisher=gigwise.com|accessdate=June 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Garvan|first1=Sinead|title=Este's Glasto shock has put her health first|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/28445875/estes-glasto-shock-has-put-her-health-first|accessdate=June 23, 2017|work=bbc.co.uk|date=July 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe single \"[[The Wire (Haim song)|The Wire]]\" was released on July 29 and the album followed on September 30.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/the-wire/id681119678?i=681119891&ign-mpt=uo%3D4|title=Haim \u2013 Days Are Gone |publisher=iTunes |date=August 5, 2013 |accessdate=August 5, 2013}}</ref> The album reached number one in the UK and has since sold 200,000 copies there.<ref name=\"UK-C\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx |title=United Kingdom Certified Awards \u2013 Haim |work=[[British Phonographic Industry]] |publisher=bpi.co.uk/certified-awards |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140625075145/http://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx |archivedate=June 25, 2014 }} (To access, enter the search term \"Haim\".)</ref><ref name=\"mclean\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/10704939/Haim-interview-Dont-call-us-a-girl-band.html|title=Haim interview: 'Don't call us a girl band'|first=Craig|last=McLean|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=March 30, 2014|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref> To promote the album, the group performed \"The Wire\" on the [[BBC]]'s ''[[The Andrew Marr Show]]'', with Este dedicating the song to the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|British Prime Minister]] [[David Cameron]], also a guest on the show.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.nme.com/news/haim/72930|title=Haim dedicate song to Prime Minister David Cameron as they meet on politics TV show|journal=New Musical Express|date=September 29, 2013|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref> The move was criticised as being ill-judged by musician [[Johnny Marr]] of [[The Smiths]], who stated that \u201cIt's really simple: they made themselves look like idiots. It's ridiculous. No-one put a gun to their head. The Conservatives tried to do the same thing with The Smiths, to re-appropriate us in a false way, to be cool by association.\u201d Haim did not respond.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigwise.com/news/87055/johnny-marr-posing-with-david-cameron-made-haim-look-like-idiots|title=Johnny Marr: 'Posing with David Cameron made Haim look like idiots'|first=Andrew|last=Trendell|work=Gigwise|date=December 18, 2013|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/showbiz/449563/Johnny-Marr-brands-Haim-idiots-over-David-Cameron-photo|title=Johnny Marr brands Haim 'idiots' over David Cameron photo|work=Daily Express|date=December 19, 2013|accessdate=June 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nHaim subsequently toured Europe throughout the remainder of 2013, recruiting touring keyboardist Tommy King,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/artists/haim|title=Haim \u2013 Biography|accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref> as well as performing as the musical guest on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' on November 23 with host [[Josh Hutcherson]]. The group performed \"The Wire\" and \"Don't Save Me\" and Este considered this performance particularly poignant as a high school drama teacher had once told her \"You're never going to be on ''Saturday Night Live''.\"<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/haim-rock-the-wire-on-snl-20131124|title=Haim Rock 'The Wire' on 'SNL'|first=Miriam|last=Coleman|journal=Rolling Stone|date=November 24, 2013|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref> The main US tour followed in April 2014 and continued into May.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5793327/haim-announces-2014-tour-dates|title=Haim Announces 2014 tour dates|first=Kevin|last=Rutherford|journal=Billboard|date=November 19, 2013|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the sisters recorded backing vocals with the [[supergroup (music)|supergroup]] [[The New Basement Tapes]] for their album ''[[Lost on the River: The New Basement Tapes|Lost on the River]]'', performing on the tracks \"Kansas City\" and \"The Whistle Is Blowing\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/lost-on-the-river-mw0002740857/credits|title=Lost on the River \u2013 The New Basement Tapes \u2013 Credits \u2013 AllMusic|website=AllMusic|accessdate=June 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mojo4music.com/17535/lost-on-the-river-the-new-basement-tapes/|title=The New Basement Tapes \u2013 Lost On The River \u2013 MOJO|date=November 19, 2014|publisher=|accessdate=June 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6319738/marcus-mumford-jim-james-elvis-costello-new-basement-tapes-bob-dylan|title=Marcus Mumford, Jim James, Elvis Costello & More Bring Bob Dylan's Lost Lyrics to Life in Concert|publisher=|accessdate=June 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2014\u20132018: Touring and ''Something to Tell You''===\n[[File:Danielle Haim - Ilosaarirock 2014.jpg|thumb|upright|Danielle Haim performing in [[Joensuu]], Finland, July 2014]]\nIn 2014, Haim were awarded the ''[[NME]]'' \"Best International Band\" award.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.nme.com/nme-video/nme-awards-2014---haim-accept-best-international-band/3269688561001|title=NME Awards 2014 \u2013 Haim Accept Best International Band|journal=New Musical Express|accessdate= October 18, 2014}}</ref> In August, the band released the video for \"[[My Song 5]]\" in a remixed version, featuring American rapper, [[A$AP Ferg]]. This is the sixth single taken from ''Days Are Gone''.<ref name=\"blistein\">{{cite journal|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/haim-asap-ferg-air-secrets-my-song-5-20140819|title=Haim and A$AP Ferg Air Their Secrets, 'Jerry Springer'-Style, in 'My Song 5' Video|first=Jon|last=Blistein|journal=Rolling Stone|date=August 19, 2014|accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref> Haim and [[Jon Heder]] made an appearance for the music video of [[Chromeo]]'s \"Old 45's\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/56907-chromeo-hang-with-haim-and-napoleon-dynamites-jon-heder-in-their-old-45s-video/|title=Chromeo Hang With Haim and Napoleon Dynamite's Jon Heder in Their \"Old 45's\" Video|first=Evan|last=Minsker|work=Pitchfork|date=September 30, 2014|accessdate=November 29, 2014}}</ref> In October, the group recorded a cover of Fleetwood Mac's \"[[Rhiannon (song)|Rhiannon]]\" with [[Stevie Nicks]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/video/t-magazine/100000003160452/rhiannon-by-stevie-nicks-and-haim.html?smid=pl-share|title='Rhiannon' by Stevie Nicks and Haim|work=New York Times|date=October 6, 2014|accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref> They continued to record their second album, having written a bulk of new material while on tour over the year.<ref name=\"blistein\"/> The band is also featured on the [[The Hunger Games: Mockingjay, Part 1 \u2013 Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|original soundtrack]] of ''[[The Hunger Games: Mockingjay \u2013 Part 1]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1970037/kanye-haim-pusha-t-charlie-xcx-mockingjay-soundtrack/|author=Gil Kaufman|date=October 21, 2014|accessdate=January 7, 2015|title=Lorde's 'Mockingjay' Soundtrack Features Kanye, Haim, Pusha T And Charli XCX|publisher=MTV}}</ref> and [[The Divergent Series: Insurgent]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2015/03/02/haim-and-m83-team-insurgent-soundtrack-holes-sky|author=Miles Raymer|date=March 2, 2015|accessdate=April 1, 2015|title=Haim and M83 team up for Insurgent soundtrack with 'Holes in the Sky'|work=Entertainment Weekly}}</ref> In November, the group contributed their vocals to the track \"[[Pray to God (song)|Pray to God]]\" on [[Calvin Harris]]' fourth studio album ''[[Motion (Calvin Harris album)|Motion]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/calvin-harris/news/pray-to-god-haim-listen/|title=Calvin Harris Debuts 90s Style New Song 'Pray To God' Featuring Haim|publisher=Capital FM|date=October 30, 2014|accessdate=November 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe group have become friends with singer-songwriter [[Taylor Swift]], and together they have visited [[Santa Catalina Island, California|Catalina]] and [[Maui]], Hawaii.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Jocelyn Vena|title=See Taylor Swift's Picture Perfect Day with Lorde, Haim|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6436473/see-taylor-swifts-picture-perfect-day-with-lorde-haim|website=Billboard|accessdate=January 24, 2015|date=January 10, 2015}}</ref> In the summer of 2015, Haim opened for Taylor Swift at select dates on [[The 1989 World Tour]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/taylor-swift-recruits-haim-for-select-1989-tour-dates-20150201|author=Daniel Kreps|date=February 1, 2015|accessdate=February 3, 2015|title=Taylor Swift Recruits Haim for Select 1989 Tour Dates|work=Rolling Stone}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/watch-taylor-swift-nelly-and-haim-perform-hot-in-herre-in-st-louis-20150930|author=Daniel Kreps|date=September 30, 2015|accessdate=October 23, 2015|title=Watch Taylor Swift, Nelly and Haim Perform 'Hot in Herre' in St. Louis|work=Rolling Stone}}</ref> The group were nominated for Best New Artist at the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/artist/haim|title=Haim|publisher=Grammy Awards|accessdate=February 8, 2015}}</ref> Danielle was injured in an accident just before the awards, but shortly afterwards [[twitter|tweeted]] that she was recovering.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/events/grammys-2015/6465521/danielle-haim-grammys-car-accident|title=Haim's Danielle Haim Misses Grammy Parties After Car Accident|journal=Billboard|date=February 8, 2015|accessdate=February 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, Haim released a teaser announcing new music and a new tour for that summer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BDjf25Ij2UM/|title=New songs. New Show. This Summer|publisher=Haim's official Instagram |date=March 29, 2016|accessdate=March 30, 2016}}</ref> In an interview with ''NME'' on January 18, 2017, Haim announced their second album will be released that summer.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/new-haim-album-release-date-tour-dates-title-artwork-everything-we-know-so-far-1949453|title=New Haim album: release date, what it sounds like and everything we know|date=January 18, 2017|work=NME|access-date=March 16, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> In April, a teaser video shot by Paul Thomas Anderson was released of a new song, \"Right Now\" from their second album, ''[[Something to Tell You]]'', released on July 7. Its [[lead single]], \"[[Want You Back (Haim song)|Want You Back]]\", was released on May 3.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.nme.com/news/music/haim-unveil-new-single-video-right-now-announce-new-album-something-tell-2061107|title=Haim unveil new single & video \"Right Now\", and announce new album \"Something To Tell You\"|magazine=NME|accessdate=April 27, 2017}}</ref> The band followed up the release with various promotional appearances, including a return appearance on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', where they performed \"Want You Back\" and \"Little of Your Love\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tarnoff|first1=Brooke|title=Watch Haim Perform 'Little of Your Love' and 'Want You Back' on 'SNL'|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/7793080/haim-snl|website=billboard.com|accessdate=May 14, 2017}}</ref> In early 2018, Haim announced the [[Sister Sister Sister Tour]] for the United States,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2018/01/haim-north-american-tour/|title=Haim Announce North American Tour|author=|date=January 18, 2018|website=spin.com|accessdate=March 7, 2018}}</ref> Europe<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://faroutmagazine.co.uk/haim-announce-details-of-european-tour/|title=HAIM announce details of European tour {{!}} Far Out Magazine|website=faroutmagazine.co.uk|access-date=June 4, 2018}}</ref> and the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/haim-detail-headlining-sister-sister-sister-tour-w515575|title=Haim Detail Headlining 'Sister Sister Sister' Tour|journal=Rolling Stone|date=January 18, 2018|accessdate=March 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2018\u2013present: ''Women in Music, Pt. III''===\nOn November 11, 2018, the group performed at Vetsaid 2018, within a lineup alongside [[Ringo Starr]], [[James Taylor]] and [[Don Henley]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://americanservicedogs.org/joe-walsh-announces-lineup-for-vetsaid-2018/|title=JOE WALSH ANNOUNCES LINEUP FOR VETSAID 2018|date=July 27, 2018|website=American Service Dogs Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=March 9, 2019}}</ref> On March 6, 2019, the band announced they were headlining the 14th annual [[Pitchfork Music Festival]] in Chicago alongside headliners [[Robyn (singer)|Robyn]] and [[The Isley Brothers]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/HAIMtheband?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Eauthor|title=HAIM (@HAIMtheband) {{!}} Twitter|website=twitter.com|language=en|access-date=March 9, 2019}}</ref> On April 4, 2019, Danielle announced via the band's social media pages that the band had been recording new music and were preparing for a summer 2019 release.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/Bv2OAv1lNUS/|title=HAIM (@haimtheband) \u2022 Instagram photos and videos|website=instagram.com|language=en|access-date=April 5, 2019}}</ref> Danielle contributed extensively to ''[[Father of the Bride (album)|Father of the Bride]]'', the fourth studio album by [[Vampire Weekend]]. In July 2019, they released the song \"[[Summer Girl (Haim song)|Summer Girl]]\", which was inspired by producer and Danielle's partner Ariel Rechtshaid's fight with cancer. They stated shortly afterwards that more music will be released in the coming months with the single \"[[Now I'm in It]]\" being released on October 30.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pace |first1=Lilly |title=Haim Reveal Emotional Battle With Depression in New Song & Video 'Now I'm In It' |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8541569/haim-now-im-in-it-video |website=Billboard |accessdate=November 11, 2019}}</ref> Haim also released another new single, \"Hallelujah\", on November 18.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/haim-new-song-hallelujah-913535/|title=Haim Get Intimate With New Song 'Hallelujah'|last=Martoccio|first=Angie|date=November 18, 2019|website=Rolling Stone|access-date=February 5, 2020}}</ref> On March 2, 2020, the band shared that their third album, ''[[Women in Music Pt. III]]'', will be released on April 24, with promotional single \"The Steps\" set to be released March 2.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/HAIMtheband/status/1234510740804947968|title=order up. our new album Women In Music Pt.III out 4/24/20. cover shot by PTA. produced by d, @matsor and @arielrechtshaid \"the steps\" out tomorrow. https://HAIM.lnk.to/WIMP3\u00a0pic.twitter.com/lD4WYNvvCz|date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> On March 23, the band announced their intentions to delay the release of the album until August 21, due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus outbreak]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/haim-delay-new-album-release-due-to-coronavirus/|title=HAIM Delay New Album Release Due to Coronavirus|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n==Musical style==\n[[File:Este Haim - Ilosaarirock 2014 1.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Este Haim.<ref name=\"Guardian20121124\" />]]\nHaim has been compared to the 1970s [[soft-rock]] band [[Fleetwood Mac]], though the group says they are \"squeamish\" about this comparison and insist they are influenced by more recent music.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.nme.com/news/haim/76220|title=Haim say they feel 'squeamish' about Fleetwood Mac comparisons|journal=New Musical Express|date=March 20, 2014|accessdate=November 10, 2014}}</ref> According to ''Metro'', their music sounds like folk-rock \"with a few R&B/hip-hop stylings thrown in for good measure\".<ref name=\"METRO\">{{cite news|last=Westbrook|first=Caroline|title=Who are Haim? Top 10 facts about BBC Sound of 2013 winners|url=http://metro.co.uk/2013/01/04/who-are-haim-top-10-facts-about-bbc-sound-of-2013-winners-3338012/|work=Metro|accessdate=January 21, 2013}}</ref> The group are fans of, and have been influenced by [[Beyonc\u00e9]], covering her song \"[[XO (song)|XO]]\" on [[BBC Radio 1]]'s \"Live Lounge\",<ref name=\"mclean\"/> and described \"My Song 5\" as \"ripping off\" [[Timbaland]].<ref name=\"weiner\"/>\n\nThe group has rejected the \"girl band\" label, preferring to be respected as musicians on their individual merits. Alana stated, \"When people call us a girl band, I take it as an insult \u2013 being a girl in a band shouldn't be a thing.\u201d<ref name=\"mclean\"/> All three sisters are proficient on more than one instrument: Este plays both guitar and bass, Danielle plays guitar and drums, and Alana plays guitar, keyboards and percussion.<ref name=\"Shalom\" /> For live performances, Este plays bass, Danielle plays lead guitar and sings lead vocals, and Alana plays rhythm guitar along with keyboards and percussion. All three sisters contribute [[vocal harmony|three part vocal harmony]].<ref name=\"lester\">{{cite news |first=Paul |last=Lester |title=New band of the day: Haim |newspaper=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/mar/23/new-band-haim |date=March 23, 2012 |accessdate=December 12, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Shalom\" />\n\nThe band's live sound is different to that in the studio. Writing for ''NME'', Hazel Sheffield said that ''Days Are Gone'' \"may confuse those won over by their raw, rocking live shows.\"<ref name=\"nmedog\"/> Recordings demonstrate the group's vocal pop style, while the group plays typical rock material such as Fleetwood Mac's \"[[Oh Well (song)|Oh Well]]\" in concert.<ref name=\"mccormick\"/> The group's background in wedding bands from their days as Rockinhaim has led them to cover many different songs live and for radio sessions, including [[Miley Cyrus]]' \"[[Wrecking Ball (Miley Cyrus song)|Wrecking Ball]]\", [[Sheryl Crow]]'s \"[[Strong Enough (Sheryl Crow song)|Strong Enough]]\" and the Strokes' \"I'll Try Anything Once\" (an early version of \"You Only Live Once\").<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2013/09/26/haim_covers_miley_cyrus_sheryl_crow_the_strokes_fleetwood_mac_mustang_sally.html|title=Haim Is Pop's Most Brilliant New Cover Band|first=Forrest|last=Wickman|journal=Slate Magazine|date=September 26, 2013|accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.nme.com/news/haim/69497|title=Haim cover The Strokes' 'I'll Try Anything Once'|journal=NME|date=April 1, 2013|accessdate=September 3, 2015}}</ref>  Este acts as the group's [[MC]] onstage, announcing most of the songs.<ref name=\"mccormick\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/10343226/Haim-interview.html|title=Haim interview|first=Neil|last=McCormick|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=September 30, 2013|accessdate=October 20, 2014}}</ref> Many of her on stage antics, such as her blunt and coarse banter with the audience, frequent [[illeism]] and her facial expressions (known as the \"bass face\") while playing are staples of the band's live shows and, to a lesser extent, the band's public image.<ref name=\"Guardian20121124\" />\n\nHutton left the band in 2017 in order to focus on his own projects. As of May 2017, the touring members are drummer Jody Giachello and keyboardist Tommy King.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ryzik|first=Melena|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/06/arts/music/haim-something-to-tell-you-interview.html|title=Haim Wants to Prove That Vintage Vibes Feel Just Fine Now|date=July 6, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=July 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Hutton has said that Este is his favourite bassist to play with. Though he declines to appear in press and publicity photos, he is nevertheless a full-time member of the band.<ref name=\"salon\"/> -->\n{{clear}}\n\n==Reception==\nCritical reaction to Haim has mostly been positive. ''[[PopMatters]]''{{'}} Matt James wrote \"It'd be hard to truly dislike Haim. They're an eminently likeable, albeit slightly kooky, trio whose story already bears the frisson of legend.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/175596-haim-days-are-gone/|title=Haim: ''Days Are Gone'' [album review] |work=[[PopMatters]] |last=James |first=Matt |date=October 1, 2013 |accessdate=October 3, 2013}}</ref> Writing for ''[[The Guardian]]'', Alexis Petridis praised the band's songwriting abilities, saying it \"has a certain kind of glossily depthless pop perfection down pat\".<ref name=\"petridis\"/> The band's sound has been described as \"nu-folk-meets-nineties-R&B\"<ref name=\"Vogue\">{{cite news |first=Freddie |last=Campion |title=Band of the Week: HAIM |newspaper=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] |location=New York City |url=http://www.vogue.com/culture/article/band-of-the-week-haim/#1 |date=February 28, 2012 |accessdate=December 12, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130912190320/http://www.vogue.com/culture/article/band-of-the-week-haim/#1 |archivedate=September 12, 2013  }}</ref> and \"music that sounds like it was written on a lakeside retreat attended by [[Stevie Nicks]], [[John Waite]] and [[En Vogue]]\".<ref name=\"Guardian20121124\">{{cite news |first=Sam |last=Wolfson |title=Haim: 'Next time, why don't you come to Los Angeles?' |at=The Guide ''supplement''|work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London, England |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/nov/24/haim-london-ellie-goulding |date=November 24, 2012 |accessdate=December 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn her survey of pop music in 2013, ''[[The Observer|Observer]]'' critic [[Kitty Empire]] praised the band for \"using the vector of harmonies to splice R&B with 1970s soft rock. They laid waste, too, to a herd of ghastly old hobby horses about guitar bands being unmarketable and record sales only being tied to women's state of undress.\"<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2013/dec/22/best-pop-music-2013-review| title = The best pop of 2013: Kitty Empire's choice| author = Empire, Kitty| date = December 22, 2013| accessdate = January 6, 2013| newspaper = The Guardian}}</ref> ''[[The Independent]]'' was more ambivalent about the band, saying there was \"an insubstantiality at their core\" of their music, as they \"plug[ged] unashamedly\" into the heritage of acts such as [[Fleetwood Mac]] and [[The Bangles]], ultimately finding Haim as \"Okay, but not much more\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-review-haim-days-are-gone-polydor-8842277.html|title=Album review: Haim, Days Are Gone (Polydor) |work=[[The Independent]] |last=Gill |first=Andy |date=September 30, 2013 |accessdate=October 3, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131003115200/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-review-haim-days-are-gone-polydor-8842277.html |archivedate=October 3, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Haim discography}}\n* ''[[Days Are Gone]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Something to Tell You]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Women in Music Pt. III]]'' (2020)<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Tours==\n===Headlining===\n* Days Are Gone Tour (2013\u20132014) <small> (supported by [[Tennis (band)|Tennis]], [[MSMR]], [[Bleached (band)|Bleached]], [[Jungle (band)|Jungle]], and [[Shy Girls]]) </small>\n*Something To Tell You Tour (2017)\n*[[Sister Sister Sister Tour]] (2018) <small>(supported by [[Lizzo]], [[Maggie Rogers]], and Grace Carter) </small>\n\n===Opening act===\n* [[The xx]] \u2013 Coexist Tour (2012)\n* [[Twin Shadow]] \u2013 Confess Tour (2012)\n* [[Florence and the Machine]] \u2013 [[Ceremonials Tour]] (2012)\n* [[Mumford and Sons]] \u2013 Gentlemen of the Road Tour (2012\u20132013)\n* [[Vampire Weekend]] \u2013 Modern Vampires Tour (2013)\n* [[Of Monsters and Men]] \u2013 My Head Is an Animal Tour (2013)\n* [[The Killers]] \u2013 [[Battle Born World Tour]] (2013)\n* [[Rihanna]] \u2013 [[Diamonds World Tour]] (2013)\n* [[Phoenix (band)|Phoenix]] \u2013 Bankrupt! Tour (2013\u20132014)\n* [[Kings of Leon]] \u2013 [[Mechanical Bull Tour]] (2014)\n* [[Taylor Swift]] \u2013 [[1989 World Tour]] (2015)\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of awards and nominations received by Haim]]\n\n==References==\n'''Footnotes'''\n{{notelist}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Haim}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.allmusic.com/artist/haim-mn0003051113 Artist page at AllMusic]\n* {{twitter|HAIMtheband}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box| before = [[Michael Kiwanuka]] | title = [[Sound of...]] | years = 2013| after = [[Sam Smith (singer)|Sam Smith]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Haim}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Haim (band)| ]]\n[[Category:Sibling musical trios]]\n[[Category:All-female bands]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Jewish American musicians]]\n[[Category:Jewish musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Family musical groups]]\n[[Category:American contemporary R&B musical groups]]\n[[Category:Rock music groups from California]]\n[[Category:American pop music groups]]\n[[Category:2006 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:American pop rock music groups]]\n[[Category:American soft rock music groups]]\n[[Category:NME Awards winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American pop rock band}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Haim\n| background       = group_or_band\n| image            = Haim Way Out West 2013.jpg\n| landscape        = yes\n| caption          = Haim performing at the [[Way Out West (festival)|Way Out West]] festival in [[Gothenburg]], Sweden, in 2013.<br/>From left: Alana, Danielle, Este Haim\n| alias            = \n| origin           = [[San Fernando Valley]], [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| genre            = <!-- Only seperate with commas per [[Template:Infobox musical artist]]. -->{{hlist|[[Rock music|Rock]]|[[soft rock]]|[[pop rock]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]}} <!-- DO NOT CHANGE GENRE WITHOUT SEEKING DISCUSSION AND ACHIEVING CONSENSUS ON THE ARTICLE TALK PAGE.  -->\n| years_active     = {{Start date|2007}}\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|[[Roc Nation]]|[[Polydor Records|Polydor]]|[[Columbia Records|Columbia]]}}\n| associated_acts  =\n| website          = {{URL|haimtheband.com}}\n| current_members  = * Este Haim\n* Danielle Haim\n* Alana Haim\n}}\n\n'''Haim''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|h|a\u026a|\u026a|m}} {{respell|HY|im}},<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JW2HaLoxPTw |title=Pronunciation Guide: HAIM Teach You How To Say Their Name |via=[[YouTube]] |date=November 21, 2013 |accessdate=July 30, 2014}}</ref>{{efn|According to the band, an English approximation of the original Hebrew, meaning \"life\", can be \"high-im\"<ref name=\"lamont\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/sep/22/haim-sisters-days-gone-interview|title=Haim: 'Dad would be like, Let's go and jam in the living room|first=Tom|last=Lamont|newspaper=The Observer|date=September 22, 2013|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref>}} stylized in [[all caps]]) is an American [[pop rock]] band from Los Angeles. The band consists of three sisters: Este Haim (bass guitar and vocals), Danielle Haim (vocals and guitar) and Alana Haim (guitars, keyboards, and vocals). In addition to their primary instruments, each member is also proficient in several others. The group's pop sound on their studio work stands in contrast to the more rock-based music of their live shows.\n\nThe sisters grew up in a musical family, and began playing instruments from an early age in the [[cover band]] Rockinhaim, fronted by their parents, [[Mordechai Haim|Moti]] and Donna. The two elder sisters, Este and Danielle, began performing with the pop group Valli Girls in 2005. They released a few songs on soundtrack and compilation albums under that name, but left the group shortly after an appearance at the 2005 [[Nickelodeon Kids' Choice Awards]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thefader.com/2013/06/25/haim-best-friends-forever|title=Haim: Best Friends Forever|work=The FADER|access-date=October 19, 2017|language=en}}</ref> They formed Haim with younger sister Alana in 2007, but did not seriously consider it a professional career for some years. After Danielle became a successful touring guitarist, first with [[Jenny Lewis]] and later with [[Julian Casablancas]], Haim reformed as a full-time operation in 2012.\n\nThe group's first release, ''Forever'' (an EP released as a limited-time download), combined with positive reception at the [[South by Southwest]] festival, led to a deal with [[Polydor Records]] and a management deal with [[Jay-Z]]'s [[Roc Nation]] group in mid-2012. The band began recording material for their first album, ''[[Days Are Gone]]'', in sessions between touring dates, including appearances at the [[Glastonbury Festival]]. The album charted in the top ten in several countries, including the number-one spot in the UK, and the group had won several \"best of\" awards by the end of 2013. The group was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]] at the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards]]. Their second album, ''[[Something to Tell You]]'', was released in July 2017.<ref name=nyt>{{cite news |last=Reznick |first=Melissa |date=July 6, 2017 |title= Haim Wants to Prove That Vintage Vibes Feel Just Fine Now|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/06/arts/music/haim-something-to-tell-you-interview.html |work=New York Times |location= New York|access-date=July 6, 2017}}</ref>  Their forthcoming third album, titled ''[[Women in Music Pt. III]]'', is scheduled for release on August 21, 2020.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early career===\n[[File:Danielle Haim Way Out West 2013 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Danielle Haim at [[Way Out West (festival)|Way Out West]] 2013 in [[Gothenburg, Sweden]]]]\nThe three sisters, '''Este Arielle Haim''' (born March 14, 1986), '''Danielle Sari Haim''' (born February 16, 1989) and '''Alana Mychal Haim''' (born December 15, 1991) were all born and raised in the [[San Fernando Valley]], [[California]], and are [[Jewish]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejc.com/news/world-news/96586/jewish-singers-haim-tipped-sound-2013|title=Jewish singers Haim tipped as Sound of 2013|newspaper=The Jewish Chronicle}}]</ref>  Their [[Israeli people|Israeli]]-born father [[Mordechai Haim|Mordechai]] (\"Moti\") and their mother Donna were both musical; though he had been a professional soccer player in Israel, Moti also played drums, while Donna won a contest on ''[[The Gong Show]]'' in the 1970s singing a [[Bonnie Raitt]] song.<ref name=\"salon\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.spin.com/featured/haim-spin-2013-october-cover-story|title=Falling for Haim|magazine=Spin|first=Camille|last=Dodero|date=September 30, 2013|accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Vogue\"/><ref name=\"lester\"/> While Danielle showed an aptitude for the guitar at a young age, Moti made the decision that Este would be more suited to the bass, buying her a second hand [[Fender bass|Fender]] for $50.<ref name=\"weiner\"/> The siblings were encouraged to listen to their parents' 1970s [[classic rock]] and [[Americana (music)|Americana]] records and, during their childhood, the family formed a band called Rockinhaim to play cover versions at local charity fairs, with Moti on drums and Donna on guitar.<ref name=\"Vogue\" /><ref name=\"Guardian20121124\" /><ref name=\"Interview\">{{cite web |first=Emma |last=Brown |title=Discovery: HAIM |work=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]] |url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/music/discovery-haim |accessdate= December 12, 2012}}</ref> The group played typical wedding band material, including [[the Beatles]]' \"[[Get Back]]\", [[Billy Joel]]'s \"[[You May Be Right (song)|You May Be Right]]\" and [[Van Morrison]]'s \"[[Brown Eyed Girl]]\",<ref name=\"Evening Standard\"/> but only did free community and benefit gigs at churches, schools and hospitals.<ref name=\"salon\"/>\n\nDanielle and Este were members of the pop-rock group the Valli Girls, and appeared on the soundtrack to the 2005 film ''[[The Sisterhood of the Traveling Pants (film)|The Sisterhood of the Traveling Pants]]''.<ref name=\"weiner\"/> Their song \"Valli Nation\" by the \"SoCal teen prodigies\" appeared on the 2005 [[Nickelodeon Kids' Choice Awards]] soundtrack alongside established musicians [[Avril Lavigne]], [[Alicia Keys]], [[Simple Plan]] and [[Good Charlotte]].<ref name=\"PRnewswire\">{{cite news |title=So-Cal Teen Prodigies The Valli Girls Launch Pop-Rock Campaign |publisher=[[Columbia Records]] |location=New York City |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/so-cal-teen-prodigies-the-valli-girls-launch-pop-rock-campaign-54307652.html |date=April 14, 2005 |accessdate=January 11, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130815021942/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/so-cal-teen-prodigies-the-valli-girls-launch-pop-rock-campaign-54307652.html |archive-date=August 15, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Este Haim Way Out West 2013 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Este Haim at Way Out West 2013 in Gothenburg, Sweden]]\nAs they grew older, the sisters became more interested in incorporating pop and [[contemporary R&B]] into their music, and in 2007 they decided to form their own band.<ref name=\"weiner\">{{cite journal|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/how-haims-three-geeky-sisters-became-the-years-coolest-new-band-20131112|title=How Haim's Three Geeky Sisters Became the Year's Coolest New Band|first=Jonah|last=Weiner|journal=Rolling Stone|date=November 12, 2013|accessdate=October 20, 2014}}</ref> For their first gig, the trio played at a Jewish deli in Hollywood and were paid in [[matzah ball soup]].<ref name=\"Independent\">{{cite news |first=Barry |last=Egan |title=Music: Haim \u2013 Sisters of super sounds |newspaper=The Independent|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/music/music-haim-sisters-of-super-sounds-29739021.html |date=November 10, 2013 |accessdate=May 19, 2014}}</ref> Early gigs were sparsely populated; Danielle recalled, \"We were [at the] bottom of the bill at 50-capacity venues and no one would show up.\"<ref name=\"mccormick\"/>\n\nFor the next five years, Haim played local venues but did not consider music as a professional career, because all three sisters were busy with other projects. Este was studying at [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]] and graduated in 2010 with a degree in Ethnomusicology (completed in just two years instead of the normal five),<ref name=\"Guardian20121124\" /><ref name=\"Evening Standard\">{{cite news |first=David |last=Smyth |title=Soundcheck: Haim |newspaper=[[Evening Standard]] |location=London, England |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/arts/music/soundcheck-haim-7682181.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130505044758/http://www.standard.co.uk/arts/music/soundcheck-haim-7682181.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=May 5, 2013 |date=April 27, 2012 |accessdate=January 9, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"Shalom\" /> specializing in Bulgarian and Brazilian music.<ref name=\"Evening Standard\"/>\n\n===Danielle Haim's guest appearances===\nAfter graduating from high school, Danielle was spotted by musician [[Jenny Lewis]] at a jam session in [[Laurel Canyon]], which led to Danielle joining Lewis' touring band.<ref name=\"weiner\"/> [[The Strokes]]' singer [[Julian Casablancas]] came to see one of Lewis's shows on tour, and he in turn asked Danielle to play guitar and percussion on his solo tour.<ref name=\"Interview\" /> Danielle rehearsed with Casablancas' band every day for two months, which she later described as \"an eye-opening experience.\"<ref name=\"Evening Standard\"/> Following working with Casablancas from late 2009 to mid 2010, she auditioned for a place in [[Scarlet Fever (band)|Scarlet Fever]], the all-female backing band for [[CeeLo Green]]. Danielle performed only once with the group, on [[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://jennylsq.libsyn.com/danielle-haim-lisa-left-eye-lopes|title=Danielle Haim // Lisa \"Left-Eye\" Lopes|last=Eliscu|first=Jenny|date=May 23, 2018|work=LSQ|access-date=July 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWhile Danielle enjoyed touring, she decided she would prefer to perform her own music alongside her sisters,<ref name=\"Evening Standard\"/> turning down a lucrative tour deal with Green.<ref name=\"mccormick\"/> Casablancas advised Danielle to write stronger material and focus on recording, as it would improve their online presence.<ref name=\"weiner\"/>\n\n===2012\u201313: ''Forever'' and commercial success===\n[[File:Alana Haim Way Out West 2013 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Alana Haim at Way Out West 2013 in Gothenburg, Sweden]]\nAfter playing shows supporting [[Edward Sharpe and the Magnetic Zeros]], [[The Henry Clay People]] and [[Kesha]], Haim released the [[Extended play|EP]] ''Forever,'' which included three songs in February 2012 as a time-limited free download on their website. Dash Hutton officially joined as drummer at the EP's release party at the Los Angeles Bootleg Theatre.<ref name=\"salon\"/> He is the son of [[Three Dog Night]]'s [[Danny Hutton]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20122666,00.html|title=Rock on|work=people.com}}</ref> and knew Este socially after she had seen his old band, [[Wires on Fire]].<ref name=\"salon\"/><ref name=\"Shalom\">{{cite web|first=Ashley |last=Baylen |title=Exclusive Interview With the Girls of 'HAIM' |work=Shalom Life |url=http://www.shalomlife.com/culture/18222/exclusive-interview-with-the-girls-of-haim/ |date=November 7, 2012 |accessdate=December 12, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121130092519/http://www.shalomlife.com/culture/18222/exclusive-interview-with-the-girls-of-haim/ |archivedate=November 30, 2012 }}</ref> The EP received attention from the music industry following a successful series of shows at the [[South by Southwest]] festival in March.<ref>''Music Week'' staff. (June 1, 2012). \"The Playlist\", ''[[Music Week]]''. (22):6</ref> Danielle recalled the first show was \"maybe a disaster\", but the remainder of the shows attracted more attention.<ref name=\"Evening Standard\"/> The band subsequently signed a deal with [[Polydor Records]] in the UK in June.<ref>{{cite news |title=Polydor UK Signs Haim |url=http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/polydor-uk-signs-haim/049252 |newspaper=[[Music Week]] |location=London, England |date=June 19, 2012 |accessdate=December 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn July, independent record label National Anthem re-released the ''Forever'' EP on 10\" vinyl, containing the original three songs along with a fourth track, a remix of \"Forever\" by [[Dan Lissvik]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Cragg |title=New music: Haim \u2013 Forever |newspaper=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2012/jun/07/new-music-haim-forever |date=June 7, 2012 |accessdate=January 9, 2013}}</ref> Following dates supporting [[Mumford & Sons]] on their Gentlemen of the Road tour in the US in August,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/08/02/mumford-and-sons-babel-new-songs-music_n_1733617.html|title=Mumford & Sons And 'Babel': Band Performs New Songs At Hoboken Concert (VIDEO)|work=The Huffington post|date=August 2, 2012|accessdate=February 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The Maccabees, Gogol Bordello, Haim, St Vincent to play Mumford and Sons' US mini-festivals |newspaper=[[NME]]|location=London, England |url=http://www.nme.com/news/mumford-and-sons/64063 |date=May 30, 2012 |accessdate=December 12, 2012}}</ref> Haim toured the UK for the first time in November 2012<ref>{{cite news |title=Haim announce debut UK tour \u2013 ticket details |newspaper=NME |url=http://www.nme.com/news/haim/65803 |date=August 29, 2012 |accessdate=December 12, 2012}}</ref> and then supported [[Florence and the Machine]] on their UK and Ireland tour in December.<ref>{{cite web |title=Florence & The Machine confirm O2 Dublin 2012 live concert date for Wednesday December 12th! |url=http://musicscene.ie/2012/09/florence-the-machine-confirm-o2-dublin-2012-live-concert-date-for-wednesday-december-12th/ |work=Music Scene |date=September 10, 2012 |accessdate=December 12, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Ben |last=Homewood |title=Haim To Support Florence + The Machine |newspaper=[[The Fly (magazine)|The Fly]] |location=London, England |url=http://www.the-fly.co.uk/news/article/1015499/haim-to-support-florence-the-machine/ |date=September 13, 2012 |accessdate=December 12, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121028022457/http://www.the-fly.co.uk/news/article/1015499/haim-to-support-florence-the-machine/ |archive-date=October 28, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBritish music magazine ''[[New Musical Express]]'' made the title track of the ''Forever'' EP its number 4 track of 2012.<ref>{{cite news |title=Albums and Tracks of the Year for 2012 |newspaper=NME |url=http://www.nme.com/bestalbumsandtracksoftheyear/2012 |date=December 2, 2012 |accessdate=December 12, 2012}}</ref> On January 4, 2013, the [[BBC]] announced that Haim had topped their annual [[Sound of...|Sound of 2013]] music industry poll to find the most promising new musical acts for the coming year.<ref name=\"so13\">{{cite web |first=Ian |last=Youngs |title=Haim top BBC Sound of 2013 list |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-20900614 |date=January 4, 2013 |accessdate=January 9, 2013}}</ref> The group also signed a management contract with the conglomerate [[Roc Nation]], returned to South by SouthWest in March 2013<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-25419364|title=Haim: Sound of 2013 winners look back|first=Mark|last=Savage|work=BBC News|date=January 3, 2014|accessdate=February 11, 2014}}</ref> and earned their own \"At Your Request\" video feature on [[Idolator (website)|Idolator]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Adickman|first=Erika Brooks|title=HAIM's \"Don't Save Me\": At Your Request|url=http://idolator.com/7446604/haim-dont-save-me-at-your-request|work=Idolator|accessdate=March 14, 2013}}</ref> In early 2013, they were featured on American recording artist [[Kid Cudi]]'s third studio album ''[[Indicud]]'', on the song titled \"Red Eye\".<ref name=\"indicud\">{{cite news|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/03/kid-cudi-unveils-indicud-album-art-and-tracklist|title=Kid Cudi Unveils \"Indicud\" Album Art and Tracklist|last=Weiss|first=Sam|date=March 26, 2013|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|accessdate=March 27, 2013}}</ref> Danielle Haim appeared on the first track, \"You're No Good\", from [[Major Lazer]]'s second album, ''[[Free the Universe]]'', alongside [[Santigold]], [[Vybz Kartel]] and Yasmin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/free-the-universe-mw0002413340|title=Free The Universe|first=David|last=Jeffries|work=AllMusic|accessdate=October 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2013\u201314: ''Days Are Gone''===\n[[File:Danielle Haim performing.png|thumb|left|upright|Danielle Haim performing in [[Indio, California]], April 2014]]\nThe group spent a year recording their first album, ''[[Days Are Gone]]'', in sessions between live shows.<ref name=\"weiner\"/> The group experimented with [[drum machine]]s and the music program [[GarageBand]], adding [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] influences to their existing sound.<ref name=\"weiner\"/> Polydor recommended producers [[Ariel Rechtshaid]] and [[James Ford (musician)|James Ford]] to help with the album, who suggested further use of [[synthesizer]]s, bringing the album closer to a straightforward pop style.<ref name=\"nmedog\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/haim/14835|title=Haim \u2013 'Days Are Gone'|first=Hazel|last=Sheffield|journal=New Musical Express|date=September 30, 2013|accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref> Several of the drum tracks were recorded with [[gated reverb]], made famous by [[Phil Collins]].<ref name=\"petridis\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/sep/26/haim-days-are-gone-review|title=Haim: Days Are Gone \u2013 review|first=Alexis|last=Petridis|newspaper=The Guardian|date=September 26, 2013|accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref> In June 2013, the group performed at [[Glastonbury Festival]], and in addition to their own set, the band appeared with [[Primal Scream]] performing background vocals on \"It's Alright, It's OK\", \"Rocks\" and \"[[Come Together]]\".<ref name=\"lamont\"/>  The band later returned for a repeat performance at Glastonbury in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/events/errnc8/acts/azf4wh#p021sfd2|title=Glastonbury 2014 \u2013 Haim|work=BBC Music|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref> After their set, Este nearly had a [[diabetic]] seizure. She has [[Type 1 diabetes]] and was diagnosed with it in 2000.<ref>{{cite news|title=Este Haim discusses type 1 diabetes and performing at T in the Park 2014|url=http://www.diabetes.co.uk/news/2014/jul/este-haim-discusses-type-1-diabetes-and-performing-at-t-in-the-park-2014-90803920.html|accessdate=June 23, 2017|work=diabetes.co.uk|date=July 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Trendell|first1=Andrew|title=ESTE HAIM: 'I ALMOST DIED AT GLASTONBURY|url=http://www.gigwise.com/news/92895/este-haim-i-almost-died-from-diabetes-at-glastonbury|date=July 24, 2014|publisher=gigwise.com|accessdate=June 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Garvan|first1=Sinead|title=Este's Glasto shock has put her health first|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/28445875/estes-glasto-shock-has-put-her-health-first|accessdate=June 23, 2017|work=bbc.co.uk|date=July 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe single \"[[The Wire (Haim song)|The Wire]]\" was released on July 29 and the album followed on September 30.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/the-wire/id681119678?i=681119891&ign-mpt=uo%3D4|title=Haim \u2013 Days Are Gone |publisher=iTunes |date=August 5, 2013 |accessdate=August 5, 2013}}</ref> The album reached number one in the UK and has since sold 200,000 copies there.<ref name=\"UK-C\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx |title=United Kingdom Certified Awards \u2013 Haim |work=[[British Phonographic Industry]] |publisher=bpi.co.uk/certified-awards |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140625075145/http://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx |archivedate=June 25, 2014 }} (To access, enter the search term \"Haim\".)</ref><ref name=\"mclean\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/10704939/Haim-interview-Dont-call-us-a-girl-band.html|title=Haim interview: 'Don't call us a girl band'|first=Craig|last=McLean|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=March 30, 2014|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref> To promote the album, the group performed \"The Wire\" on the [[BBC]]'s ''[[The Andrew Marr Show]]'', with Este dedicating the song to the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|British Prime Minister]] [[David Cameron]], also a guest on the show.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.nme.com/news/haim/72930|title=Haim dedicate song to Prime Minister David Cameron as they meet on politics TV show|journal=New Musical Express|date=September 29, 2013|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref> The move was criticised as being ill-judged by musician [[Johnny Marr]] of [[The Smiths]], who stated that \u201cIt's really simple: they made themselves look like idiots. It's ridiculous. No-one put a gun to their head. The Conservatives tried to do the same thing with The Smiths, to re-appropriate us in a false way, to be cool by association.\u201d Haim did not respond.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigwise.com/news/87055/johnny-marr-posing-with-david-cameron-made-haim-look-like-idiots|title=Johnny Marr: 'Posing with David Cameron made Haim look like idiots'|first=Andrew|last=Trendell|work=Gigwise|date=December 18, 2013|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/showbiz/449563/Johnny-Marr-brands-Haim-idiots-over-David-Cameron-photo|title=Johnny Marr brands Haim 'idiots' over David Cameron photo|work=Daily Express|date=December 19, 2013|accessdate=June 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nHaim subsequently toured Europe throughout the remainder of 2013, recruiting touring keyboardist Tommy King,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/artists/haim|title=Haim \u2013 Biography|accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref> as well as performing as the musical guest on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' on November 23 with host [[Josh Hutcherson]]. The group performed \"The Wire\" and \"Don't Save Me\" and Este considered this performance particularly poignant as a high school drama teacher had once told her \"You're never going to be on ''Saturday Night Live''.\"<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/haim-rock-the-wire-on-snl-20131124|title=Haim Rock 'The Wire' on 'SNL'|first=Miriam|last=Coleman|journal=Rolling Stone|date=November 24, 2013|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref> The main US tour followed in April 2014 and continued into May.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5793327/haim-announces-2014-tour-dates|title=Haim Announces 2014 tour dates|first=Kevin|last=Rutherford|journal=Billboard|date=November 19, 2013|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the sisters recorded backing vocals with the [[supergroup (music)|supergroup]] [[The New Basement Tapes]] for their album ''[[Lost on the River: The New Basement Tapes|Lost on the River]]'', performing on the tracks \"Kansas City\" and \"The Whistle Is Blowing\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/lost-on-the-river-mw0002740857/credits|title=Lost on the River \u2013 The New Basement Tapes \u2013 Credits \u2013 AllMusic|website=AllMusic|accessdate=June 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mojo4music.com/17535/lost-on-the-river-the-new-basement-tapes/|title=The New Basement Tapes \u2013 Lost On The River \u2013 MOJO|date=November 19, 2014|publisher=|accessdate=June 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6319738/marcus-mumford-jim-james-elvis-costello-new-basement-tapes-bob-dylan|title=Marcus Mumford, Jim James, Elvis Costello & More Bring Bob Dylan's Lost Lyrics to Life in Concert|publisher=|accessdate=June 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2014\u20132018: Touring and ''Something to Tell You''===\n[[File:Danielle Haim - Ilosaarirock 2014.jpg|thumb|upright|Danielle Haim performing in [[Joensuu]], Finland, July 2014]]\nIn 2014, Haim were awarded the ''[[NME]]'' \"Best International Band\" award.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.nme.com/nme-video/nme-awards-2014---haim-accept-best-international-band/3269688561001|title=NME Awards 2014 \u2013 Haim Accept Best International Band|journal=New Musical Express|accessdate= October 18, 2014}}</ref> In August, the band released the video for \"[[My Song 5]]\" in a remixed version, featuring American rapper, [[A$AP Ferg]]. This is the sixth single taken from ''Days Are Gone''.<ref name=\"blistein\">{{cite journal|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/haim-asap-ferg-air-secrets-my-song-5-20140819|title=Haim and A$AP Ferg Air Their Secrets, 'Jerry Springer'-Style, in 'My Song 5' Video|first=Jon|last=Blistein|journal=Rolling Stone|date=August 19, 2014|accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref> Haim and [[Jon Heder]] made an appearance for the music video of [[Chromeo]]'s \"Old 45's\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/56907-chromeo-hang-with-haim-and-napoleon-dynamites-jon-heder-in-their-old-45s-video/|title=Chromeo Hang With Haim and Napoleon Dynamite's Jon Heder in Their \"Old 45's\" Video|first=Evan|last=Minsker|work=Pitchfork|date=September 30, 2014|accessdate=November 29, 2014}}</ref> In October, the group recorded a cover of Fleetwood Mac's \"[[Rhiannon (song)|Rhiannon]]\" with [[Stevie Nicks]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/video/t-magazine/100000003160452/rhiannon-by-stevie-nicks-and-haim.html?smid=pl-share|title='Rhiannon' by Stevie Nicks and Haim|work=New York Times|date=October 6, 2014|accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref> They continued to record their second album, having written a bulk of new material while on tour over the year.<ref name=\"blistein\"/> The band is also featured on the [[The Hunger Games: Mockingjay, Part 1 \u2013 Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|original soundtrack]] of ''[[The Hunger Games: Mockingjay \u2013 Part 1]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1970037/kanye-haim-pusha-t-charlie-xcx-mockingjay-soundtrack/|author=Gil Kaufman|date=October 21, 2014|accessdate=January 7, 2015|title=Lorde's 'Mockingjay' Soundtrack Features Kanye, Haim, Pusha T And Charli XCX|publisher=MTV}}</ref> and [[The Divergent Series: Insurgent]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2015/03/02/haim-and-m83-team-insurgent-soundtrack-holes-sky|author=Miles Raymer|date=March 2, 2015|accessdate=April 1, 2015|title=Haim and M83 team up for Insurgent soundtrack with 'Holes in the Sky'|work=Entertainment Weekly}}</ref> In November, the group contributed their vocals to the track \"[[Pray to God (song)|Pray to God]]\" on [[Calvin Harris]]' fourth studio album ''[[Motion (Calvin Harris album)|Motion]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/calvin-harris/news/pray-to-god-haim-listen/|title=Calvin Harris Debuts 90s Style New Song 'Pray To God' Featuring Haim|publisher=Capital FM|date=October 30, 2014|accessdate=November 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe group have become friends with singer-songwriter [[Taylor Swift]], and together they have visited [[Santa Catalina Island, California|Catalina]] and [[Maui]], Hawaii.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Jocelyn Vena|title=See Taylor Swift's Picture Perfect Day with Lorde, Haim|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6436473/see-taylor-swifts-picture-perfect-day-with-lorde-haim|website=Billboard|accessdate=January 24, 2015|date=January 10, 2015}}</ref> In the summer of 2015, Haim opened for Taylor Swift at select dates on [[The 1989 World Tour]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/taylor-swift-recruits-haim-for-select-1989-tour-dates-20150201|author=Daniel Kreps|date=February 1, 2015|accessdate=February 3, 2015|title=Taylor Swift Recruits Haim for Select 1989 Tour Dates|work=Rolling Stone}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/watch-taylor-swift-nelly-and-haim-perform-hot-in-herre-in-st-louis-20150930|author=Daniel Kreps|date=September 30, 2015|accessdate=October 23, 2015|title=Watch Taylor Swift, Nelly and Haim Perform 'Hot in Herre' in St. Louis|work=Rolling Stone}}</ref> The group were nominated for Best New Artist at the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/artist/haim|title=Haim|publisher=Grammy Awards|accessdate=February 8, 2015}}</ref> Danielle was injured in an accident just before the awards, but shortly afterwards [[twitter|tweeted]] that she was recovering.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/events/grammys-2015/6465521/danielle-haim-grammys-car-accident|title=Haim's Danielle Haim Misses Grammy Parties After Car Accident|journal=Billboard|date=February 8, 2015|accessdate=February 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, Haim released a teaser announcing new music and a new tour for that summer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BDjf25Ij2UM/|title=New songs. New Show. This Summer|publisher=Haim's official Instagram |date=March 29, 2016|accessdate=March 30, 2016}}</ref> In an interview with ''NME'' on January 18, 2017, Haim announced their second album will be released that summer.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/new-haim-album-release-date-tour-dates-title-artwork-everything-we-know-so-far-1949453|title=New Haim album: release date, what it sounds like and everything we know|date=January 18, 2017|work=NME|access-date=March 16, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> In April, a teaser video shot by Paul Thomas Anderson was released of a new song, \"Right Now\" from their second album, ''[[Something to Tell You]]'', released on July 7. Its [[lead single]], \"[[Want You Back (Haim song)|Want You Back]]\", was released on May 3.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.nme.com/news/music/haim-unveil-new-single-video-right-now-announce-new-album-something-tell-2061107|title=Haim unveil new single & video \"Right Now\", and announce new album \"Something To Tell You\"|magazine=NME|accessdate=April 27, 2017}}</ref> The band followed up the release with various promotional appearances, including a return appearance on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', where they performed \"Want You Back\" and \"Little of Your Love\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tarnoff|first1=Brooke|title=Watch Haim Perform 'Little of Your Love' and 'Want You Back' on 'SNL'|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/7793080/haim-snl|website=billboard.com|accessdate=May 14, 2017}}</ref> In early 2018, Haim announced the [[Sister Sister Sister Tour]] for the United States,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2018/01/haim-north-american-tour/|title=Haim Announce North American Tour|author=|date=January 18, 2018|website=spin.com|accessdate=March 7, 2018}}</ref> Europe<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://faroutmagazine.co.uk/haim-announce-details-of-european-tour/|title=HAIM announce details of European tour {{!}} Far Out Magazine|website=faroutmagazine.co.uk|access-date=June 4, 2018}}</ref> and the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/haim-detail-headlining-sister-sister-sister-tour-w515575|title=Haim Detail Headlining 'Sister Sister Sister' Tour|journal=Rolling Stone|date=January 18, 2018|accessdate=March 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2018\u2013present: ''Women in Music, Pt. III''===\nOn November 11, 2018, the group performed at Vetsaid 2018, within a lineup alongside [[Ringo Starr]], [[James Taylor]] and [[Don Henley]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://americanservicedogs.org/joe-walsh-announces-lineup-for-vetsaid-2018/|title=JOE WALSH ANNOUNCES LINEUP FOR VETSAID 2018|date=July 27, 2018|website=American Service Dogs Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=March 9, 2019}}</ref> On March 6, 2019, the band announced they were headlining the 14th annual [[Pitchfork Music Festival]] in Chicago alongside headliners [[Robyn (singer)|Robyn]] and [[The Isley Brothers]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/HAIMtheband?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Eauthor|title=HAIM (@HAIMtheband) {{!}} Twitter|website=twitter.com|language=en|access-date=March 9, 2019}}</ref> On April 4, 2019, Danielle announced via the band's social media pages that the band had been recording new music and were preparing for a summer 2019 release.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/Bv2OAv1lNUS/|title=HAIM (@haimtheband) \u2022 Instagram photos and videos|website=www.instagram.com|language=en|access-date=April 5, 2019}}</ref> Danielle contributed extensively to ''[[Father of the Bride (album)|Father of the Bride]]'', the fourth studio album by [[Vampire Weekend]]. In July 2019, they released the song \"[[Summer Girl (Haim song)|Summer Girl]]\", which was inspired by producer and Danielle's partner Ariel Rechtshaid's fight with cancer. They stated shortly afterwards that more music will be released in the coming months with the single \"[[Now I'm in It]]\" being released on October 30.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pace |first1=Lilly |title=Haim Reveal Emotional Battle With Depression in New Song & Video 'Now I'm In It' |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8541569/haim-now-im-in-it-video |website=Billboard |accessdate=November 11, 2019}}</ref> Haim also released another new single, \"Hallelujah\", on November 18.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/haim-new-song-hallelujah-913535/|title=Haim Get Intimate With New Song 'Hallelujah'|last=Martoccio|first=Angie|date=November 18, 2019|website=Rolling Stone|access-date=February 5, 2020}}</ref> On March 2, 2020, the band shared that their third album, ''[[Women in Music Pt. III]]'', will be released on April 24, with promotional single \"The Steps\" set to be released March 2.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/HAIMtheband/status/1234510740804947968|title=order up. our new album Women In Music Pt.III out 4/24/20. cover shot by PTA. produced by d, @matsor and @arielrechtshaid \"the steps\" out tomorrow. https://HAIM.lnk.to/WIMP3\u00a0pic.twitter.com/lD4WYNvvCz|date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> On March 23, the band announced their intentions to delay the release of the album until August 21, due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus outbreak]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/haim-delay-new-album-release-due-to-coronavirus/|title=HAIM Delay New Album Release Due to Coronavirus|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n==Musical style==\n[[File:Este Haim - Ilosaarirock 2014 1.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Este Haim.<ref name=\"Guardian20121124\" />]]\nHaim has been compared to the 1970s [[soft-rock]] band [[Fleetwood Mac]], though the group says they are \"squeamish\" about this comparison and insist they are influenced by more recent music.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.nme.com/news/haim/76220|title=Haim say they feel 'squeamish' about Fleetwood Mac comparisons|journal=New Musical Express|date=March 20, 2014|accessdate=November 10, 2014}}</ref> According to ''Metro'', their music sounds like folk-rock \"with a few R&B/hip-hop stylings thrown in for good measure\".<ref name=\"METRO\">{{cite news|last=Westbrook|first=Caroline|title=Who are Haim? Top 10 facts about BBC Sound of 2013 winners|url=http://metro.co.uk/2013/01/04/who-are-haim-top-10-facts-about-bbc-sound-of-2013-winners-3338012/|work=Metro|accessdate=January 21, 2013}}</ref> The group are fans of, and have been influenced by [[Beyonc\u00e9]], covering her song \"[[XO (song)|XO]]\" on [[BBC Radio 1]]'s \"Live Lounge\",<ref name=\"mclean\"/> and described \"My Song 5\" as \"ripping off\" [[Timbaland]].<ref name=\"weiner\"/>\n\nThe group has rejected the \"girl band\" label, preferring to be respected as musicians on their individual merits. Alana stated, \"When people call us a girl band, I take it as an insult \u2013 being a girl in a band shouldn't be a thing.\u201d<ref name=\"mclean\"/> All three sisters are proficient on more than one instrument: Este plays both guitar and bass, Danielle plays guitar and drums, and Alana plays guitar, keyboards and percussion.<ref name=\"Shalom\" /> For live performances, Este plays bass, Danielle plays lead guitar and sings lead vocals, and Alana plays rhythm guitar along with keyboards and percussion. All three sisters contribute [[vocal harmony|three part vocal harmony]].<ref name=\"lester\">{{cite news |first=Paul |last=Lester |title=New band of the day: Haim |newspaper=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/mar/23/new-band-haim |date=March 23, 2012 |accessdate=December 12, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Shalom\" />\n\nThe band's live sound is different to that in the studio. Writing for ''NME'', Hazel Sheffield said that ''Days Are Gone'' \"may confuse those won over by their raw, rocking live shows.\"<ref name=\"nmedog\"/> Recordings demonstrate the group's vocal pop style, while the group plays typical rock material such as Fleetwood Mac's \"[[Oh Well (song)|Oh Well]]\" in concert.<ref name=\"mccormick\"/> The group's background in wedding bands from their days as Rockinhaim has led them to cover many different songs live and for radio sessions, including [[Miley Cyrus]]' \"[[Wrecking Ball (Miley Cyrus song)|Wrecking Ball]]\", [[Sheryl Crow]]'s \"[[Strong Enough (Sheryl Crow song)|Strong Enough]]\" and the Strokes' \"I'll Try Anything Once\" (an early version of \"You Only Live Once\").<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2013/09/26/haim_covers_miley_cyrus_sheryl_crow_the_strokes_fleetwood_mac_mustang_sally.html|title=Haim Is Pop's Most Brilliant New Cover Band|first=Forrest|last=Wickman|journal=Slate Magazine|date=September 26, 2013|accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.nme.com/news/haim/69497|title=Haim cover The Strokes' 'I'll Try Anything Once'|journal=NME|date=April 1, 2013|accessdate=September 3, 2015}}</ref>  Este acts as the group's [[MC]] onstage, announcing most of the songs.<ref name=\"mccormick\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/10343226/Haim-interview.html|title=Haim interview|first=Neil|last=McCormick|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=September 30, 2013|accessdate=October 20, 2014}}</ref> Many of her on stage antics, such as her blunt and coarse banter with the audience, frequent [[illeism]] and her facial expressions (known as the \"bass face\") while playing are staples of the band's live shows and, to a lesser extent, the band's public image.<ref name=\"Guardian20121124\" />\n\nHutton left the band in 2017 in order to focus on his own projects. As of May 2017, the touring members are drummer Jody Giachello and keyboardist Tommy King.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ryzik|first=Melena|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/06/arts/music/haim-something-to-tell-you-interview.html|title=Haim Wants to Prove That Vintage Vibes Feel Just Fine Now|date=July 6, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=July 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Hutton has said that Este is his favourite bassist to play with. Though he declines to appear in press and publicity photos, he is nevertheless a full-time member of the band.<ref name=\"salon\"/> -->\n{{clear}}\n\n==Reception==\nCritical reaction to Haim has mostly been positive. ''[[PopMatters]]''{{'}} Matt James wrote \"It'd be hard to truly dislike Haim. They're an eminently likeable, albeit slightly kooky, trio whose story already bears the frisson of legend.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/175596-haim-days-are-gone/|title=Haim: ''Days Are Gone'' [album review] |work=[[PopMatters]] |last=James |first=Matt |date=October 1, 2013 |accessdate=October 3, 2013}}</ref> Writing for ''[[The Guardian]]'', Alexis Petridis praised the band's songwriting abilities, saying it \"has a certain kind of glossily depthless pop perfection down pat\".<ref name=\"petridis\"/> The band's sound has been described as \"nu-folk-meets-nineties-R&B\"<ref name=\"Vogue\">{{cite news |first=Freddie |last=Campion |title=Band of the Week: HAIM |newspaper=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] |location=New York City |url=http://www.vogue.com/culture/article/band-of-the-week-haim/#1 |date=February 28, 2012 |accessdate=December 12, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130912190320/http://www.vogue.com/culture/article/band-of-the-week-haim/#1 |archivedate=September 12, 2013  }}</ref> and \"music that sounds like it was written on a lakeside retreat attended by [[Stevie Nicks]], [[John Waite]] and [[En Vogue]]\".<ref name=\"Guardian20121124\">{{cite news |first=Sam |last=Wolfson |title=Haim: 'Next time, why don't you come to Los Angeles?' |at=The Guide ''supplement''|work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London, England |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/nov/24/haim-london-ellie-goulding |date=November 24, 2012 |accessdate=December 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn her survey of pop music in 2013, ''[[The Observer|Observer]]'' critic [[Kitty Empire]] praised the band for \"using the vector of harmonies to splice R&B with 1970s soft rock. They laid waste, too, to a herd of ghastly old hobby horses about guitar bands being unmarketable and record sales only being tied to women's state of undress.\"<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2013/dec/22/best-pop-music-2013-review| title = The best pop of 2013: Kitty Empire's choice| author = Empire, Kitty| date = December 22, 2013| accessdate = January 6, 2013| newspaper = The Guardian}}</ref> ''[[The Independent]]'' was more ambivalent about the band, saying there was \"an insubstantiality at their core\" of their music, as they \"plug[ged] unashamedly\" into the heritage of acts such as [[Fleetwood Mac]] and [[The Bangles]], ultimately finding Haim as \"Okay, but not much more\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-review-haim-days-are-gone-polydor-8842277.html|title=Album review: Haim, Days Are Gone (Polydor) |work=[[The Independent]] |last=Gill |first=Andy |date=September 30, 2013 |accessdate=October 3, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131003115200/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-review-haim-days-are-gone-polydor-8842277.html |archivedate=October 3, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Haim discography}}\n* ''[[Days Are Gone]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Something to Tell You]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Women in Music Pt. III]]'' (2020)<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Tours==\n===Headlining===\n* Days Are Gone Tour (2013\u20132014) <small> (supported by [[Tennis (band)|Tennis]], [[MSMR]], [[Bleached (band)|Bleached]], [[Jungle (band)|Jungle]], and [[Shy Girls]]) </small>\n*Something To Tell You Tour (2017)\n*[[Sister Sister Sister Tour]] (2018) <small>(supported by [[Lizzo]], [[Maggie Rogers]], and Grace Carter) </small>\n\n===Opening act===\n* [[The xx]] \u2013 Coexist Tour (2012)\n* [[Twin Shadow]] \u2013 Confess Tour (2012)\n* [[Florence and the Machine]] \u2013 [[Ceremonials Tour]] (2012)\n* [[Mumford and Sons]] \u2013 Gentlemen of the Road Tour (2012\u20132013)\n* [[Vampire Weekend]] \u2013 Modern Vampires Tour (2013)\n* [[Of Monsters and Men]] \u2013 My Head Is an Animal Tour (2013)\n* [[The Killers]] \u2013 [[Battle Born World Tour]] (2013)\n* [[Rihanna]] \u2013 [[Diamonds World Tour]] (2013)\n* [[Phoenix (band)|Phoenix]] \u2013 Bankrupt! Tour (2013\u20132014)\n* [[Kings of Leon]] \u2013 [[Mechanical Bull Tour]] (2014)\n* [[Taylor Swift]] \u2013 [[1989 World Tour]] (2015)\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of awards and nominations received by Haim]]\n\n==References==\n'''Footnotes'''\n{{notelist}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Haim}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.allmusic.com/artist/haim-mn0003051113 Artist page at AllMusic]\n* {{twitter|HAIMtheband}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box| before = [[Michael Kiwanuka]] | title = [[Sound of...]] | years = 2013| after = [[Sam Smith (singer)|Sam Smith]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Haim}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Haim (band)| ]]\n[[Category:Sibling musical trios]]\n[[Category:All-female bands]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Jewish American musicians]]\n[[Category:Jewish musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Family musical groups]]\n[[Category:American contemporary R&B musical groups]]\n[[Category:Rock music groups from California]]\n[[Category:American pop music groups]]\n[[Category:2006 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:American pop rock music groups]]\n[[Category:American soft rock music groups]]\n[[Category:NME Awards winners]]\n", "name_user": "Kahtar", "label": "safe", "comment": "Repair CS1 error(s), replaced: website=www. \u2192 website=", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haim_(band)"}
{"title_page": "Sebastian Jones (filmmaker)", "text_new": "'''Sebastian Jones''' is an American [[film director]], [[screenwriter]], and [[Film editor|editor]]. He is best known for his documentary film ''[[Everybody's Everything (film)|Everybody's Everything]]'' (2019), which chronicles the life of [[Lil Peep]]. Jones is a frequent collaborator and prot\u00e9g\u00e9 of [[Terrence Malick]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/lil-peep-in-talks-for-movie-role-before-fatal-overdose-1203159841/|title=Lil Peep Was in Talks for Movie Role Before Fatal Overdose|last=Donnelly|first=Matt|last2=Donnelly|first2=Matt|date=2019-03-11|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> \n\n<br />\n\n== Life and career ==\nJones grew up in South Florida and studied film at the University of Central Florida before moving to Austin, Texas to work with Terrence Malick.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://schedule.sxsw.com/2019/speakers/2010049|title=Sebastian Jones|website=SXSW 2020 Schedule|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> He worked as an editor and eventually associate producer on Malick projects like ''[[Knight of Cups (film)|Knight of Cups]]'' starring Christian Bale and ''[[Song to Song]]'' with Ryan Gosling and Cate Blanchett.<ref name=\":0\" /> He was also an editor on ''[[Voyage of Time]]'' and ''[[A Hidden Life (2019 film)|A Hidden Life]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-hidden-life-review-mournful-memorable-and-emotionally-exhilarating-11576185486|title=\u2018A Hidden Life\u2019 Review: Mournful, Memorable and Emotionally Exhilarating|last=Anderson|first=John|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, after seeing Lil Peep perform in Austin, Texas., Jones became interested in casting him in a feature film. Instead, Peep died just a few days later, and Jones was later tapped by Malick to co-direct a posthumous documentary on Peep's life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/movies/lil-peep-everybodys-everything-documentary-1.38248331|title=New documentary chronicles life of LI's Lil Peep|website=Newsday|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> While researching for the film, Jones came across an Instagram post, which Peep published the day before his death, captioned: \u201cI just wana be everybody\u2019s everything.\u201d This led to the film's title ''Everybody's Everything''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2019/11/lil-peep-documentary-everybodys-everything-interview/|title=Dreamer Boy: Lil Peep \u2018Everybody\u2019s Everything\u2019 Directors on His Complex Life and Legacy|date=2019-11-15|website=Spin|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> The film premiered at [[South by Southwest]] in March 2019 to critical acclaim.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/03/sxsw-best-films-tv-2019-booksmart-beach-bum-1202051505/|title=SXSW 2019: The 10 Best Film and TV Projects at the Festival|last=O'Falt|first=Eric Kohn,Ben Travers,Kate Erbland,Chris|last2=Kohn|first2=Eric|date=2019-03-16|website=IndieWire|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11|last3=Travers|first3=Ben|last4=Erbland|first4=Kate|last5=O'Falt|first5=Chris}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/09/lil-peep-documentary-everybodys-everything-trailer|title=Watch the New Trailer for Lil Peep Documentary 'Everybody's Everything'|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> It was acquired by Gunpowder & Sky and released later that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/lil-peep-everybody-everything-gunpowdersky-documentary-1202610573/|title=\u2018Everybody\u2019s Everything\u2019 Documentary Of Rapper Lil Peep Goes Worldwide To Gunpowder & Sky|last=Haring|first=Bruce|last2=Haring|first2=Bruce|date=2019-05-09|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nJones has described his approach as mixing documentary and narrative elements.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/lil-peep-directors-film-interview-908550/|title=Lil Peep Film Directors Talk Doc's Toughest Moments and Interviews as 'Therapy Sessions'|last=Wang|first=Amy X.|last2=Wang|first2=Amy X.|date=2019-11-06|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n<br />\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{IMDb name|id=3758612}}\n", "text_old": "'''Sebastian Jones''' is an American [[film director]], [[screenwriter]], and [[Film editor|editor]]. He is best known for his documentary film ''[[Everybody's Everything (film)|Everybody's Everything]]'' (2019), which chronicles the life of [[Lil Peep]]. Jones is a frequent collaborator and prot\u00e9g\u00e9 of [[Terrence Malick]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/lil-peep-in-talks-for-movie-role-before-fatal-overdose-1203159841/|title=Lil Peep Was in Talks for Movie Role Before Fatal Overdose|last=Donnelly|first=Matt|last2=Donnelly|first2=Matt|date=2019-03-11|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> \n\n<br />\n\n== Life and career ==\nJones grew up in South Florida and studied film at the University of Central Florida before moving to Austin, Texas to work with Terrence Malick.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://schedule.sxsw.com/2019/speakers/2010049|title=Sebastian Jones|website=SXSW 2020 Schedule|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> He worked as an editor and eventually associate producer on Malick projects like ''[[Knight of Cups (film)|Knight of Cups]]'' starring Christian Bale and ''[[Song to Song]]'' with Ryan Gosling and Cate Blanchett.<ref name=\":0\" /> He was also an editor on ''[[Voyage of Time]]'' and ''[[A Hidden Life (2019 film)|A Hidden Life]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-hidden-life-review-mournful-memorable-and-emotionally-exhilarating-11576185486|title=\u2018A Hidden Life\u2019 Review: Mournful, Memorable and Emotionally Exhilarating|last=Anderson|first=John|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, after seeing Lil Peep perform in Austin, Texas., Jones became interested in casting him in a feature film. Instead, Peep died just a few days later, and Jones was later tapped by Malick to co-direct a posthumous documentary on Peep's life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/movies/lil-peep-everybodys-everything-documentary-1.38248331|title=New documentary chronicles life of LI's Lil Peep|website=Newsday|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> While researching for the film, Jones came across an Instagram post, which Peep published the day before his death, captioned: \u201cI just wana be everybody\u2019s everything.\u201d This led to the film's title ''Everybody's Everything''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2019/11/lil-peep-documentary-everybodys-everything-interview/|title=Dreamer Boy: Lil Peep \u2018Everybody\u2019s Everything\u2019 Directors on His Complex Life and Legacy|date=2019-11-15|website=Spin|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> The film premiered at [[South by Southwest]] in March 2019 to critical acclaim.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/03/sxsw-best-films-tv-2019-booksmart-beach-bum-1202051505/|title=SXSW 2019: The 10 Best Film and TV Projects at the Festival|last=O'Falt|first=Eric Kohn,Ben Travers,Kate Erbland,Chris|last2=Kohn|first2=Eric|date=2019-03-16|website=IndieWire|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11|last3=Travers|first3=Ben|last4=Erbland|first4=Kate|last5=O'Falt|first5=Chris}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2019/09/lil-peep-documentary-everybodys-everything-trailer|title=Watch the New Trailer for Lil Peep Documentary 'Everybody's Everything'|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> It was acquired by Gunpowder & Sky and released later that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/lil-peep-everybody-everything-gunpowdersky-documentary-1202610573/|title=\u2018Everybody\u2019s Everything\u2019 Documentary Of Rapper Lil Peep Goes Worldwide To Gunpowder & Sky|last=Haring|first=Bruce|last2=Haring|first2=Bruce|date=2019-05-09|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nJones describes his approach as mixing documentary and narrative elements.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/lil-peep-directors-film-interview-908550/|title=Lil Peep Film Directors Talk Doc's Toughest Moments and Interviews as 'Therapy Sessions'|last=Wang|first=Amy X.|last2=Wang|first2=Amy X.|date=2019-11-06|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n<br />\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{IMDb name|id=3758612}}\n", "name_user": "Luckycharmander", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sebastian_Jones_(filmmaker)"}
{"title_page": "National College of Cyber Security", "text_new": "{{coord|51.999211|-0.740948|type:edu_region:GB-MIK|format=dms|display=title}}\n{{citation style|date=May 2017}}\n{{infobox organization\n|key_people=[[Alastair MacWillson]]<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news|author=Eleanor Ross |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/nov/24/college-of-national-security-teenage-codebreakers-school-open-bletchley-park |title=School for teenage codebreakers to open in Bletchley Park &#124; Technology |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date= |accessdate=2016-12-12}}</ref><ref name=\"ibtimes\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/uks-first-cybersecurity-college-open-historic-bletchley-park-1593212 |title=UK's first National College of Cyber Security to open at historic Bletchley Park |website=Ibtimes.co.uk |date=2016-11-24 |accessdate=2016-12-12}}</ref><ref name=\"wired\">{{cite web|author=Tom Mendelsohn |url=https://arstechnica.com/business/2016/11/cyber-college-wannabe-codebreakers-earmarked-bletchley-park-site/ |title=Cyber college for wannabe codebreakers planned at UK\u2019s iconic Bletchley Park |publisher=Ars Technica |date=2016-11-25 |accessdate=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n|name=College of National Security<ref name=\"guardian\" /><ref name=\"ibtimes\" /><ref name=\"wired\" /> (or National College of Cyber Security)<ref name=\"pcworld\">{{cite web|last=Sayer |first=Peter |url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/3144553/security/britains-wartime-codebreaking-base-could-host-a-national-cyber-security-college.html |title=Britain's wartime codebreaking base could host a national cyber security college |publisher=PCWorld |date=2016-11-24 |accessdate=2016-12-12}}</ref><ref name=\"sky\">{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/story/enigma-codebreaker-site-to-house-cyber-security-college-10669638 |title=Enigma Codebreaker site to house cyber security college |website=News.sky.com |date=2016-11-25 |accessdate=2016-12-23}}</ref><ref name=\"mkcitizen\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.miltonkeynes.co.uk/our-region/milton-keynes/central-mk/bletchley-park-reactivated-with-planned-national-college-of-cyber-security-on-site-1-7693997 |title=Bletchley Park reactivated with planned National College of Cyber Security on site - Milton Keynes Citizen |website=Miltonkeynes.co.uk |date=2016-11-24 |accessdate=2016-12-23}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web|last=Coughlan |first=Sean |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-38065563 |title=Bletchley Park: 'Codebreakers school' planned for site |publisher=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=2016-12-23}}</ref><ref name=\"musjournal\">{{cite web|url=https://www.museumsassociation.org/museums-journal/news/30112016-national-museum-of-computing-involved-in-setting-up-cyber-security-training-college |title=National Museum of Computing involved in setting up cyber security college |publisher=Museums Association |date=2016-11-30 |accessdate=2016-12-23}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''College of National Security'''<ref name=\"guardian\" /><ref name=\"ibtimes\" /><ref name=\"wired\" /> (also referred to as the '''National College of Cyber Security'''<ref name=\"pcworld\" /><ref name=\"sky\" /><ref name=\"mkcitizen\" /><ref name=\"bbc\" /><ref name=\"musjournal\" />) was a proposed [[cyber security]] school for 16-19 year-olds, scheduled to open in September 2020<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qufaro.uk/news/christmas-update|title=Qufaro Christmas Update - Qufaro|website=qufaro.uk|access-date=2018-11-08}}</ref> at [[Bletchley Park]].<ref name=\"guardian\" /><ref name=\"ibtimes\" /><ref name=\"wired\" />\n\nThe initiative to create the school emerged from Qufaro,<ref name=\"pcworld\" /> a not-for-profit organisation created by representatives of [[Raytheon]], [[BT Managed Security Solutions|BT Security]], the [[Institute of Information Security Professionals]], and [[National Museum of Computing]].<ref name=\"ibtimes\" /><ref name=\"wired\" />\n\nThe college was to be located in Block G of Bletchley Park which was being renovated in 2017 with funding by the Bletchley Park Science and Innovation Centre. ([[Bletchley Park Trust]] has no involvement in the cyber security college.)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.museumsassociation.org/museums-journal/news/30112016-national-museum-of-computing-involved-in-setting-up-cyber-security-training-college|title=National Museum of Computing involved in setting up cyber security college {{!}} Museums Association|last=Sullivan|first=Nicola|date=2016-11-30|website=www.museumsassociation.org|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe opening of the college, originally planned for 2016, had been pushed back to 2020 as the application to open (as a college in the [[Department for Education|Department for Education's]] Free Schools program) had yet to be granted.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qufaro.uk/news/national-college-of-cyber-security-application-update|title=National College of Cyber Security application update - Qufaro|website=qufaro.uk|access-date=2018-11-08}}</ref>. However, in April 2020 Bletchley Park Capital Partners (a private company run by Tim Reynolds, Deputy Chairman of the National Museum of Computing) announced plans to sell off the [[freehold]] to the site for commercial development. Offers of between \u00a34m and \u00a36m were reportedly being sought for the 3 [[acre]] plot, for which planning permission for employment purposes had been granted in 2005.<ref>{{cite web |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=9 April 2020 |title=Historic Block G at Bletchley Park is being sold off for up to \u00a36m in Milton Keynes |url=https://www.miltonkeynes.co.uk/heritage-and-retro/heritage/historic-block-g-bletchley-park-being-sold-ps6m-milton-keynes-2533475 |website=Milton Keynes Citizen |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411081736/https://www.miltonkeynes.co.uk/heritage-and-retro/heritage/historic-block-g-bletchley-park-being-sold-ps6m-milton-keynes-2533475 |archive-date=11 April 2020 |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Clarence-Smith |first=Louisa |title=Bletchley Park\u2019s wartime buildings up for sale |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/bletchley-parks-wartime-buildings-up-for-sale-qxf7sn658 |website=The Times |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411050048/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/bletchley-parks-wartime-buildings-up-for-sale-qxf7sn658 |archive-date=11 April 2020 |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Higher education colleges in England]]\n\n{{UK-university-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{coord|51.999211|-0.740948|type:edu_region:GB-MIK|format=dms|display=title}}\n{{citation style|date=May 2017}}\n{{infobox organization\n|key_people=[[Alastair MacWillson]]<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news|author=Eleanor Ross |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2016/nov/24/college-of-national-security-teenage-codebreakers-school-open-bletchley-park |title=School for teenage codebreakers to open in Bletchley Park &#124; Technology |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date= |accessdate=2016-12-12}}</ref><ref name=\"ibtimes\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/uks-first-cybersecurity-college-open-historic-bletchley-park-1593212 |title=UK's first National College of Cyber Security to open at historic Bletchley Park |website=Ibtimes.co.uk |date=2016-11-24 |accessdate=2016-12-12}}</ref><ref name=\"wired\">{{cite web|author=Tom Mendelsohn |url=https://arstechnica.com/business/2016/11/cyber-college-wannabe-codebreakers-earmarked-bletchley-park-site/ |title=Cyber college for wannabe codebreakers planned at UK\u2019s iconic Bletchley Park |publisher=Ars Technica |date=2016-11-25 |accessdate=2016-12-12}}</ref>\n|name=College of National Security<ref name=\"guardian\" /><ref name=\"ibtimes\" /><ref name=\"wired\" /> (or National College of Cyber Security)<ref name=\"pcworld\">{{cite web|last=Sayer |first=Peter |url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/3144553/security/britains-wartime-codebreaking-base-could-host-a-national-cyber-security-college.html |title=Britain's wartime codebreaking base could host a national cyber security college |publisher=PCWorld |date=2016-11-24 |accessdate=2016-12-12}}</ref><ref name=\"sky\">{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/story/enigma-codebreaker-site-to-house-cyber-security-college-10669638 |title=Enigma Codebreaker site to house cyber security college |website=News.sky.com |date=2016-11-25 |accessdate=2016-12-23}}</ref><ref name=\"mkcitizen\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.miltonkeynes.co.uk/our-region/milton-keynes/central-mk/bletchley-park-reactivated-with-planned-national-college-of-cyber-security-on-site-1-7693997 |title=Bletchley Park reactivated with planned National College of Cyber Security on site - Milton Keynes Citizen |website=Miltonkeynes.co.uk |date=2016-11-24 |accessdate=2016-12-23}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web|last=Coughlan |first=Sean |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-38065563 |title=Bletchley Park: 'Codebreakers school' planned for site |publisher=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=2016-12-23}}</ref><ref name=\"musjournal\">{{cite web|url=https://www.museumsassociation.org/museums-journal/news/30112016-national-museum-of-computing-involved-in-setting-up-cyber-security-training-college |title=National Museum of Computing involved in setting up cyber security college |publisher=Museums Association |date=2016-11-30 |accessdate=2016-12-23}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''College of National Security'''<ref name=\"guardian\" /><ref name=\"ibtimes\" /><ref name=\"wired\" /> (also referred to as the '''National College of Cyber Security'''<ref name=\"pcworld\" /><ref name=\"sky\" /><ref name=\"mkcitizen\" /><ref name=\"bbc\" /><ref name=\"musjournal\" />) was a proposed [[cyber security]] school for 16-19 year-olds, scheduled to open in September 2020<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qufaro.uk/news/christmas-update|title=Qufaro Christmas Update - Qufaro|website=qufaro.uk|access-date=2018-11-08}}</ref> at [[Bletchley Park]].<ref name=\"guardian\" /><ref name=\"ibtimes\" /><ref name=\"wired\" />\n\nThe initiative to create the school emerged from Qufaro,<ref name=\"pcworld\" /> a not-for-profit organisation created by representatives of [[Raytheon]], [[BT Managed Security Solutions|BT Security]], the [[Institute of Information Security Professionals]], and [[National Museum of Computing]].<ref name=\"ibtimes\" /><ref name=\"wired\" />\n\nThe college was to be located in Block G of Bletchley Park which was being renovated in 2017 with funding by the Bletchley Park Science and Innovation Centre. ([[Bletchley Park Trust]] has no involvement in the cyber security college.)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.museumsassociation.org/museums-journal/news/30112016-national-museum-of-computing-involved-in-setting-up-cyber-security-training-college|title=National Museum of Computing involved in setting up cyber security college {{!}} Museums Association|last=Sullivan|first=Nicola|date=2016-11-30|website=www.museumsassociation.org|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe opening of the college, originally planned for 2016, had been pushed back to 2020 as the application to open (as a college in the [[Department for Education|Department for Education's]] Free Schools program) had yet to be granted<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qufaro.uk/news/national-college-of-cyber-security-application-update|title=National College of Cyber Security application update - Qufaro|website=qufaro.uk|access-date=2018-11-08}}</ref>. However, in April 2020 Bletchley Park Capital Partners (a private company run by Tim Reynolds, Deputy Chairman of the National Museum of Computing) announced plans to sell off the [[freehold]] to the site for commercial development. Offers of between \u00a34m and \u00a36m were reportedly being sought for the 3 [[acre]] plot, for which planning permission for employment purposes had been granted in 2005.<ref>{{cite web |last=Clarence-Smith |first=Louisa |title=Bletchley Park\u2019s wartime buildings up for sale |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/bletchley-parks-wartime-buildings-up-for-sale-qxf7sn658 |website=The Times |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411050048/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/bletchley-parks-wartime-buildings-up-for-sale-qxf7sn658 |archive-date=11 April 2020 |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Higher education colleges in England]]\n\n{{UK-university-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Edwin of Northumbria", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added 1 ref.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_College_of_Cyber_Security"}
{"title_page": "Bach's Missa of 1733", "text_new": "{{italic title|string=Missa}}\n[[File:Missa in B Minor (\"Kyrie\" and \"Gloria\" of the B Minor Mass) WDL11619.pdf|thumb|300px|Title page for the bundle of part [[Sheet music|scores]] of the Kyrie{{ndash}}Gloria Mass which [[Bach]] sent to [[Dresden]] in 1733. The page includes a dedication to the [[Electors of Saxony#Saxony-Poland|Saxon Elector]] and a list of voices and instruments.]]\n'''Bach's {{lang|la|Missa}} of 1733''', [[BWV]]&nbsp;232 I (early version), is a [[Kyrie\u2013Gloria Mass]] in [[B&nbsp;minor]], composed in 1733 by [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]. It is an extended [[missa brevis]] ({{lang de|Kurzmesse}}, {{literal translation|short [[Mass (music)|Mass]]}}) consisting of a [[Kyrie]] in three [[movement (music)|movement]]s and a [[Gloria in Excelsis Deo|Gloria]] in nine movements. Bach started to compose it, partly based on earlier work, after the death of his sovereign [[Augustus the Strong]] (1&nbsp;February 1733), dedicating it to the latter's son and successor, [[Frederick August II]], in a letter dated 27&nbsp;July 1733. At the time, Bach was in his tenth year as [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] church musician in [[Leipzig]], while the [[Catholic]] court of the sovereign [[Electors of Saxony#Saxony-Poland|Elector of Saxony]] was located in [[Dresden]]. Bach sent performance parts of his {{lang|la|Missa}} to Dresden while he kept the [[autograph score]] in Leipzig. Upon arrival in Dresden, the Mass was not added to the repertoire of the Catholic [[court chapel]], but instead the parts, and Bach's dedication letter, were archived in the sovereign's library.\n\nThe composition, also known as Bach's '''Mass for the Dresden court''', is an unusually extended work scored for five-part [[SATB|SSATB]] soloists and choir with an orchestra having a broad [[Wind instrument|winds section]]. After reusing some of its music in a cantata he composed around 1745 ([[BWV 191]]), Bach finally [[Mass in B minor structure|incorporated the 1733 ''Missa'' as the first of four parts]] of his [[Mass in B&nbsp;minor]], composed/assembled in the last years of his life, around 1748\u20131749. It seems unlikely that the 1733 Kyrie\u2013Gloria Mass, either in its original form or as part of the Mass in B&nbsp;minor, was ever performed during Bach's lifetime.\n\nThe Kyrie\u2013Gloria Mass was not assigned a separate number in the [[Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis|BWV catalogue]], but in order to distinguish it from the later complete mass ({{nowrap|[[BWV 232]]}}), numbers like '''{{nowrap|BWV 232a}}''' and {{nowrap|'''BWV 232<sup>I</sup>'''}} are in use.<ref name=\"Laurson\" />{{sfn|Stockigt|2013}} In 2005 [[B\u00e4renreiter]] published the Mass in the [[New Bach Edition]] series as '''{{lang|de|Missa, {{nowrap|BWV 232 I,}} Fassung von 1733}}''' (i.e. 1733 version of [[Missa, BWV&nbsp;232&nbsp;I]]), in a volume of early versions of the Mass in B&nbsp;minor.<ref name=\"B\u00e4renreiter\" /> That volume also contained early versions of the Credo (BWV 232 II) and Sanctus (BWV 232 III) of the later Mass.<ref name=\"B\u00e4renreiter\" /> Bach's Mass for the Dresden court is also referred to as '''''{{nowrap|Missa 1733}}'''''<ref name=\"Grob\" /> and \"The {{lang|la|Missa}} of 1733\".<ref name=\"Butt\" /> The [[Bach Digital]] website refers to the work as \"BWV 232/I (Fr\u00fchfassung)\", i.e. early version of [[Mass in B minor#I. Kyrie and Gloria (\"Missa\")|Part I of BWV&nbsp;232]].<ref name=\"BDW0290\">Bach Digital Work {{BDW|0290}} at {{url|www.bach-digital.de}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{See also|Bach's church music in Latin}}\nBach was a [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] church musician, devoted to the composition of sacred music in German. He wrote more than 200 [[Church cantata (Bach)|cantatas for the liturgy]], most of them in [[Leipzig]] from 1723 to 1726 at the beginning of his tenure as ''[[Thomaskantor]]'', responsible for the music at the major churches. In Leipzig, a university city where Latin was understood, musical settings of the traditional Latin texts were performed on festive holidays. Bach composed [[Bach's church music in Latin|works on Latin texts]], for example a [[Magnificat in E-flat major, BWV 243a|Magnificat]] in 1723, performed both on the Marian feast [[Visitation (Christianity)|Visitation]] and Christmas that year, and in 1724 a [[Sanctus]] for Christmas, which he later integrated into his [[Mass in B minor structure#Sanctus|Mass in B minor]].<ref name=\"Butt\" /><ref name=\"Steinitz\" /> Both works were exceptional settings: the Magnificat extended to five vocal parts and the Sanctus to six voices, when four-part singing was common in Leipzig.<ref name=\"Rathey\" />\n\n=== Bach's intentions with the composition ===\n[[Augustus the Strong]], [[List of Polish monarchs#Elective Kings of Poland (Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth)|King of Poland]] and [[Electorate of Saxony|Elector of Saxony]], died on 1 February 1733. He had converted to the [[Catholic Church]] in order to ascend to the throne of Poland in 1697. During a period of mourning, no cantata performances were permitted in Leipzig, interrupting Bach's normal work of a weekly cantata performance. Bach was free to compose a Kyrie\u2013Gloria Mass for the court of Dresden,<ref name=\"Leipzig\" /><ref name=\"Leisinger\" /> where the successor was the later [[Augustus III of Poland]]. Bach presented the parts of the works to him with a note dated 27 July 1733, in the hope of obtaining the title \"Saxon Electoral Court Composer\":\n{{quote|In deepest Devotion I present to your Royal Highness this small product of that science which I have attained in Musique, with the most humble request that you will deign to regard it not according to the imperfection of its Composition, but with a most gracious eye&nbsp;... and thus take me into your most mighty Protection.<ref name=\"Talbeck\" />}}\nA different translation of this polite understatement{{sfn|Wolff|2013|p=11}} is \"an insignificant product of the skill I have attained in music.\"<ref name=\"WDL\" /> In the note, Bach also complained that he had \"innocently suffered one injury or another\" in [[Leipzig]].<ref>An English translation of the letter is given in Hans T. David and Arthur Mendel, ''The Bach Reader: A Life of Johann Sebastian Bach in Letters and Documents'', W. W. Norton & Company, 1945, p. 128. (Also in \"The New Bach Reader: A Life of Johann Sebastian Bach in Letters and Documents\" revised by [[Christoph Wolff]], W. W. Norton & Co Inc, 1998, {{ISBN|978-0-393-04558-1}} , p. 158.)</ref> Petitions to the new ruler after the death of the previous one, as the one sent by Bach, were not exceptional in nature: similar petitions by musicians to August III included those of [[Jan Dismas Zelenka]] (unsuccessfully competing with [[Johann Adolph Hasse]] for the post of [[Kapellmeister]]),<ref name=\"Zelenka-Hasse\">[http://www.earlymusicworld.com/id16.html Dresden in the time of Zelenka and Hasse] at {{url|earlymusicworld.com}}, quoted from ''Goldberg Early Music Magazine''.</ref> [[Johann Joachim Quantz]] and [[Pantaleon Hebenstreit]] (a Lutheran court church director).{{sfn|Stockigt|2013|p= 40}} What was exceptional was that Bach accompanied his petition with a composition of considerable dimensions \u2014 a liturgical composition, no less \u2014 which was surprising in that Bach was then employed as a Lutheran church composer and was here presenting a work for the Catholic liturgy.\n[[File:LageEhemaligesOpernhausAmTaschenberg1828.jpg|thumb|500px|This detail from an 1828 map of Dresden shows the location of the [[Opernhaus am Taschenberg]], the court theatre that in the 1660s was built adjacent to the Elector's palace, then in 1708 transformed into the Catholic Hofkirche, and, by the time this map was drawn, after building the [[Hofkirche (Dresden)|Katholische Kirche]] (1739\u20131751), among others, transformed into an archive (indicated as \"'''Archiv'''\" in the middle of this picture).<ref>\"Musical chronicle of the city of Dresden.\" in Medien-Info by Dresden Marketing GmbH, 2013</ref><br />The location of the [[Sophienkirche, Dresden|Sophienkirche]] is shown in the lower part of this detail.]]\nAt the time, Germany lived under the ''[[cuius regio, eius religio]]'' principle (inhabitants of a region have to follow the religion of their ruler), which led to a somewhat double situation in Dresden under August the Strong: officially Catholic in Poland but only privately so in Dresden \u2014 no Catholicism was imposed on Lutheran Saxony, and only the court at Dresden was Catholic.{{sfn|Leaver|2013|pp=25-27}} Lutherans, including the [[Electress#Electresses of Saxony|Electress]] [[Christiane Eberhardine of Brandenburg-Bayreuth|Christiane Eberhardine]], who steadfastly refused to convert to Catholicism (and for whom Bach had composed his ''[[Trauer-Ode|Trauerode]]'' when she died in 1727),<ref name=\"Zelenka-Hasse\" /> had the [[Sophienkirche, Dresden|Sophienkirche]] as their place of worship,{{efn|Note that the Sophienkirche was not called the Hofkirche before 1737, so for the purposes of this article about a 1733 composition, \"Hofkirche\" refers exclusively to the ''Catholic'' court church housed in the former [[Opernhaus am Taschenberg]] and served by the court chapel musicians (also predating plans for the later [[Hofkirche (Dresden)|Hofkirche/Cathedral]] built between the later [[Schlo\u00dfplatz (Dresden)|Schlo\u00dfplatz]] and Theaterplatz within about half a decade).}} while the Catholic Hofkirche (Court church) was housed in the former [[Opernhaus am Taschenberg|court theatre]] from 1708.{{sfn|Leaver|2013|p=27}}\n\nLuther had not rejected any of the [[Mass (music)|five parts of the Mass ordinary that traditionally were eligible for a musical setting]] (Kyrie, Gloria, [[Nicene Creed]], Sanctus, {{nowrap|Agnus Dei}}): Protestant mass celebrations could include any of these and/or their translation in the local language.{{sfn|Leaver|2013|pp=24-25}} There is no doubt that Bach admired his ancestor [[Veit Bach|Veit]] for his Lutheranism.{{sfn|Leaver|2013|pp=}} In all probability Bach wrote a Lutheran liturgical composition that would have been just as acceptable in a Catholic mass. At least the panache with which Bach showed off as a versatile composer, only six years after openly choosing the Lutheran side at the death of the new elector's mother, must be admired.\n\nFor the music, Bach borrowed extensively from his previous cantata compositions.{{sfn|Wolff|2013|p=11}} Bach may have had the capabilities of the singers and instrumentalists of the Dresden [[court chapel]] (which served the Hofkirche) in mind when composing the piece: at the time these included [[Johann Georg Pisendel]] (violinist and [[concert master]]), Johann Christian Richter (oboist), and the flautists [[Pierre-Gabriel Buffardin]] and Johann Joachim Quantz.{{sfn|Stockigt|2013|pp=46-47}} These performers, versed in the French as well as Italian performance styles, were the best of what could be found anywhere in Europe.<ref name=\"Zelenka-Hasse\" /> The new elector's taste for the operatic genre was no secret either.<ref name=\"Zelenka-Hasse\" /> For church music the [[Neapolitan mass]] came closest to that genre, and this was the preferred Mass type at the Hofkirche.{{sfn|Stockigt|2013}} Bach was no doubt aware that apart from the excellent instrumentalists, the Dresden Hofkapelle (\"court chapel\") also had vocal soloists at its disposal (such as [[Faustina Bordoni]], the wife of [[Johann Adolph Hasse]]) who could excel in the type of arias that was customary in operas and Neapolitan masses.{{sfn|Stockigt|2013}}<ref name=\"Zelenka-Hasse\" />\n\nThe score Bach sent to Dresden consisted of the separate parts for [[Soprano]] I, Soprano II, [[Alto]], [[Tenor]], [[Bass (voice type)|Bass]], [[Trumpet]] I, Trumpet II, Trumpet III, [[Timpani]], [[Corno da caccia|Corno da Caccia]], [[Flauto traverso]] I, Flauto traverso II, [[Oboe]] ([[Oboe d'amore|d'amore]]) I, Oboe (d'amore) II, Oboe (d'amore) III, [[Violin]]s I (2 copies), Violins II, [[Viola]], [[Cello]], [[Bassoon]] and [[Basso continuo]]. Most of these copies were written by Bach himself, but for the last movements of both Kyrie and Gloria his sons [[Carl Philipp Emanuel Bach|Carl Philipp Emanuel]] (soprano parts), [[Wilhelm Friedemann Bach|Wilhelm Friedemann]] (violino I parts), and his wife [[Anna Magdalena Bach|Anna Magdalena]] (cello parts) helped, along with an anonymous copyist (oboe and basso continuo parts).<ref>[http://www.bach-digital.de/receive/BachDigitalSource_source_00002721 D-Dl Mus.2405-D-21] at Dresden, S\u00e4chsische Landesbibliothek \u2013 Staats- und Universit\u00e4tsbibliothek (University library), available online at {{url|bach-digital.de}}</ref> Performance material for the choir was not included, nor was the basso continuo part very elaborated.{{sfn|Stockigt|2013|p=53}} All these parts appear to have been copied directly from the full score, which Bach kept in Leipzig.<ref name=\"Butt\" /> Bach supplied the parts for single performers with many details that are not in the score he kept.<ref name=\"Leisinger Interview\" />\n[[File:Dresden Inneres der Hofkapelle 1719.jpg|thumb|500px|Interior of the Hofkirche (Hofkapelle){{efn|Court chapel: in this instance referring to the church building; other instances of Hofkapelle/court chapel in this article generally refer to [[chapel (music)|chapel as an ensemble of musicians]], directed by a [[chapel master]] (Kapellmeister).}} in 1719<ref>Hubert Ermisch. ''[[:File:Ermisch Das alte Archivgeb\u00e4ude am Taschenberge in Dresden.pdf|Das alte Archivgeb\u00e4ude am Taschenberge in Dresden: Ein Erinnerungsblatt]]''. Dresden: Baensch, 1888.</ref>]]\nAlthough some commentators suggest other liturgical and worldly venues where Bach may have anticipated a performance of the {{lang|la|Missa}},{{sfn|Stockigt|2013|p=41}} there seems little doubt that Bach intended to tailor the piece so that it could be performed at the Dresden Hofkirche.{{sfn|Stockigt|2013}}\n\n=== Reception at the Dresden court ===\nWhen the composition arrived in Dresden its format wasn't very unusual compared to other works performed at the time at the Hofkirche. The repertoire performed there included over thirty masses consisting of only a Kyrie and Gloria. Many of these were composed or acquired by the court composer at the time [[Jan Dismas Zelenka]]; and in most cases, as also happened with Bach's {{lang|la|Missa}}, these were later expanded into a complete mass ([[missa tota]]), or at least a Mass with all the usual Mass sections except the Credo ([[missa senza credo]]). Nor the fact that Bach's {{lang|la|Missa}} was composed for virtuoso performers, nor that it was a composition requiring a [[SATB|SSATB]] choir could be considered exceptional at the time and place.{{sfn|Stockigt|2013}}\n\nThe [[key signature]] of the mass was somewhat exceptional: the Hofkirche 1765 catalogue<ref>Janice B. Stockigt. \"\u201cCATALOGO (THEMATICO) [SIC] DELLA MUSICA DI CHIESA (CATHOLICA [SIC] IN DRESDA) COMPOSTA DA DIVERSI AUTORI \u2013 SECONDO L\u2019ALFABETTO '''1765'''\u201d: AN INTRODUCTION\"</ref> contains only one Mass in B minor, by [[Antonio Caldara]]. [[D major]], the relative major key of B minor (i.e. with the same accidentals), was the most usual key for festive music including trumpets, because of the Saxon [[natural trumpet]]: all of Zelenka's solemn masses were in that key, but also 6 of the 12 movements of Bach's {{lang|la|Missa}} (including the Christe eleison and the opening and closing movements of the Gloria) have that same key signature. The most exceptional feature of Bach's mass appears to have been its duration, which largely exceeded what was usual compared to similar compositions at the time in Dresden. This seems the most likely reason why the composition was filed in the Royal Library upon arrival in Dresden, instead of being added to the repertoire of the Hofkirche.{{sfn|Stockigt|2013}}\n\nAs for the result of his petition to the new ruler in Dresden: some three years after his request Bach received the title of Royal Court Composer.{{sfn|Stockigt|2013}} In the intermediate period the Elector had other business to attend to: the [[War of the Polish Succession#Poland|War of the Polish Succession]].\n\n=== Performance history before being integrated in the Mass in B minor, BWV 232 ===\n[[File:Dresden Sophienkirche Lithographie.jpg|thumb|[[Sophienkirche, Dresden]], possibly the location of a first performance]]\nIt is debated if the {{lang|la|Missa}} was performed at the time.<ref name=\"Butt\" /> If it was performed, the most likely venue was the Sophienkirche in Dresden, where Bach's son [[Wilhelm Friedemann Bach|Wilhelm Friedemann]] had been organist since June.<ref name=\"Butt\" /><ref>The details added in this section are from Christoph Wolff \"Bach\", III, 7 (\u00a7&nbsp;8), ''[[Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians|Grove Music Online]]'' ed., L. Macy. http://www.grovemusic.com/ . Last accessed August 9, 2007.</ref>\n\nAround 1745 Bach used three movements of the [[Gloria in excelsis Deo|Gloria]] of the {{lang|la|Missa}} of 1733 for his cantata [[Gloria in excelsis Deo, BWV 191|''Gloria in excelsis Deo'', BWV 191]].<ref name=\"Butt\" /><ref name=\"Steinitz\" />\n\n== Scoring and structure \u2014 incorporation in the Mass in B minor, BWV 232 ==\n{{Main|Mass in B minor structure}}\n\nIn the last years of his life, presumably around 1748\u20131749, Bach integrated the complete {{lang|la|Missa}} of 1733 unchanged in his [[Mass in B minor]], his only missa tota.<ref name=\"Laurson\" /> Scoring and structure are identical with the later work, but markings differ because the parts contain more details than the 1733 score which he kept. Bach made changes{{vague|date=November 2014}} to that score when he completed the mass.<ref name=\"Leisinger Interview\" />\n\nThe work is scored for five vocal parts, two [[soprano]]s, [[alto]], [[tenor]] and [[Bass (voice type)|bass]], and an [[Baroque instruments|orchestra]] of three trumpets, timpani, corno da caccia, two flauti traversi, two oboes, two oboes d'amore, two bassoons, two violins, viola, and basso continuo.\n\nThe [[Mass in B minor structure#Parts and movements|Kyrie]] is structured in three movements. Two different choral movements frame a duet for two sopranos. The [[Mass in B minor structure#Gloria|Gloria]] is structured in nine movements in a symmetric arrangement around a duet of soprano and tenor.\n\nThe {{lang|la|Missa}} of 1733 forms a considerable part of the Mass in B minor which publisher [[Hans Georg N\u00e4geli]] described in 1818 as \"the greatest musical art work of all times and nations\" when he tried a first publication.<ref name=\"WDL\" />\n\n== Publication ==\n\nIn 2005, [[B\u00e4renreiter]] published the work, titled \"Missa, BWV 232 I, Fassung von 1733\", as part of the [[Neue Bach Ausgabe]]. The editor of three ''Early Versions of the Mass BWV 232'', the others being \"Credo in unum Deum, BWV 232 II, Fr\u00fchfassung in G\" and \"Sanctus, BWV 232 III, Fassung von 1724\" was [[Uwe Wolf (musicologist)|Uwe Wolf]].<ref name=\"B\u00e4renreiter\" />\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist\n| colwidth = 30em\n| refs =\n\n<ref name=\"Leipzig\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.bach-digital.de/receive/BachDigitalWork_work_00000290?lang=en\n| title = Missa b-minor (Kyrie and Gloria of the b-minor Mass)) BWV 232 (Fr\u00fchfassung); BC E 2 / Mass\n| publisher = [[University of Leipzig]]\n| accessdate = 28 October 2014\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Butt\">{{cite book\n| last = Butt\n| first = John\n| authorlink = John Butt (musician)\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=rMZqTYkm0DwC&pg=PA9\n| title = Bach: Mass in B Minor\n| year = 1991\n| publisher = [[Cambridge University Press]]\n| isbn = 0-521-38716-7\n| pages = 8\u201312\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Grob\">{{cite web\n| last = Grob\n| first = Jochen\n| url = http://www.s-line.de/homepages/bachdiskographie/vok_lat/vok_lat_messen.html\n| title = Missa 1733\n| publisher = s-line.de\n| language = German\n| accessdate = 28 October 2014\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140819181912/http://www.s-line.de/homepages/bachdiskographie/vok_lat/vok_lat_messen.html\n| archive-date = 19 August 2014\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Laurson\">{{cite web\n| last = Laurson\n| first = Jens F.\n| url = http://www.musicweb-international.com/classrev/2009/Aug09/Bach_Missa_2564690571.htm\n| title = Johann Sebastian Bach (1685\u20131750) / Missa (1733)\n| publisher = musicweb-international.com\n| year = 2009\n| accessdate = 12 February 2013\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Leisinger\">{{cite book\n| last = Leisinger\n| first = Ulrich\n| url = http://www.carus-verlag.com/images-intern/pdf/Artikel/3123200-foreword.pdf\n| title = Foreword\n| year = 2014\n| publisher = [[Carus-Verlag]]\n| format = PDF\n| pages = IV\u2013VI\n| access-date = 2014-12-06\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141209105532/http://www.carus-verlag.com/images-intern/pdf/Artikel/3123200-foreword.pdf\n| archive-date = 2014-12-09\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Leisinger Interview\">{{cite book\n| last = Leisinger\n| first = Ulrich\n| url = http://www.carus-verlag.com/carus-magazin-01-2014-bach-h-moll-messe.en.html\n| title = \"Care is an editor's highest priority\"\n| year = 2014\n| publisher = [[Carus-Verlag]]\n| pages = IV\u2013VI\n| language = German\n| access-date = 2014-10-29\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141029114812/http://www.carus-verlag.com/carus-magazin-01-2014-bach-h-moll-messe.en.html\n| archive-date = 2014-10-29\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Rathey\">{{cite web\n| last = Rathey\n| first = Markus\n| url = http://bach.nau.edu/mass/prose/Rathey.pdf\n| title = Johann Sebastian Bach's Mass in B Minor: The Greatest Artwork of All Times and All People\n| publisher = bach.nau.edu\n| format = PDF\n| year = 2003\n| accessdate = 17 September 2013\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131005014030/http://bach.nau.edu/mass/prose/Rathey.pdf\n| archive-date = 5 October 2013\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref>\n<!-- not needed but kept here because it's mentioned on the talk\n<ref name=\"Smith\">{{cite web\n| last = Smith\n| first = Tim\n| url = http://bach.nau.edu/mass/prose/assembly.pdf\n| publisher = bach.nau.edu\n| title = Assembly of the Mass\n| format = PDF\n| accessdate = 29 October 2014\n}}</ref> -->\n\n<ref name=\"Steinitz\">{{cite web\n| last = Steinitz\n| first = Margaret\n| url = http://www.aucx96.dsl.pipex.com/Lbsdb/LBSDB_LC_INTRO.html\n| title = Bach's Latin Church Music\n| accessdate = 16 September 2010\n| publisher = [[London Bach Society]]\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110715085014/http://www.aucx96.dsl.pipex.com/Lbsdb/LBSDB_LC_INTRO.html\n| archive-date = 15 July 2011\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Talbeck\">{{cite web\n| last = Talbeck\n| first = Carol\n| url = http://www.sfchoral.org/site/bach-b-minor-mass/\n| title = Johann Sebastian Bach: Mass in B Minor / Everything must be possible. \u2013 J. S. Bach.\n| publisher = sfchoral.org\n| year = 2002\n| accessdate = 13 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"WDL\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.wdl.org/en/item/11619/\n| title = Missa in B Minor (\"Kyrie\" and \"Gloria\" of the B Minor Mass)\n| website = [[World Digital Library]]\n| accessdate = 8 August 2013\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"B\u00e4renreiter\">{{cite web\n| url = https://www.baerenreiter.com/en/search/product/?artNo=BA5293-01\n| title = Missa, BWV 232 I, Fassung von 1733, in \"Bach, Johann Sebastian / Early Versions of the Mass BWV 232\"\n| year = 2005\n| website = [[B\u00e4renreiter]]\n| accessdate = 3 November 2014\n}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== Sources ==\n\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|editor-last1=Tomita|editor-first1=Yo |editor-last2=Leaver|editor-first2=Robin A. |editor-last3=Smaczny|editor-first3=Jan |title=Exploring Bach's B-minor Mass|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZbT1AAAAQBAJ|date= 2013|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-00790-1|pp=3\u201320|first=Christoph |last=Wolff|chapter=Past, present and future perspectives on Bach's B-minor Mass}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|editor-last1=Tomita|editor-first1=Yo |editor-last2=Leaver|editor-first2=Robin A. |editor-last3=Smaczny|editor-first3=Jan |last=Leaver|first=Robin A. |title=Exploring Bach's B-minor Mass|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZbT1AAAAQBAJ|date= 2013|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-00790-1|chapter=Bach's Mass: 'Catholic' or 'Lutheran'?|pp=21\u201338}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|editor-last1=Tomita|editor-first1=Yo |editor-last2=Leaver|editor-first2=Robin A. |editor-last3=Smaczny|editor-first3=Jan |last=Stockigt |first=Janice B.|title=Exploring Bach's B-minor Mass|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZbT1AAAAQBAJ|date= 2013|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-00790-1|chapter=Bach's ''Missa'' BWV 232<sup>I</sup> in the context of Catholic Mass settings in Dresden, 1729\u20131733|pp=39\u201353}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMSLP|work=Mass in B minor, BWV 232 (Bach, Johann Sebastian)|cname=Mass in B minor, BWV 232}}\n* {{ChoralWiki|work=Mass in B minor, BWV 232 (Johann Sebastian Bach)|Mass in B minor, BWV 232}}\n\n{{Masses and Magnificats by Johann Sebastian Bach}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mass for the Dresden Court Bwv 232}}\n[[Category:Masses by Johann Sebastian Bach]]\n[[Category:1733 compositions]]\n[[Category:Compositions with natural trumpets in D]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title|string=Missa}}\n[[File:Missa in B Minor (\"Kyrie\" and \"Gloria\" of the B Minor Mass) WDL11619.pdf|thumb|300px|Title page for the bundle of part [[Sheet music|scores]] of the Kyrie{{ndash}}Gloria Mass which [[Bach]] sent to [[Dresden]] in 1733. The page includes a dedication to the [[Electors of Saxony#Saxony-Poland|Saxon Elector]] and a list of voices and instruments.]]\n'''Bach's {{lang|la|Missa}} of 1733''', [[BWV]]&nbsp;232 I (early version), is a [[Kyrie\u2013Gloria Mass]] in [[B&nbsp;minor]], composed in 1733 by [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]. It is an extended [[missa brevis]] ({{lang de|Kurzmesse}}, {{literal translation|short [[Mass (music)|Mass]]}}) consisting of a [[Kyrie]] in three [[movement (music)|movement]]s and a [[Gloria in Excelsis Deo|Gloria]] in nine movements. Bach started to compose it, partly based on earlier work, after the death of his sovereign [[Augustus the Strong]] (1&nbsp;February 1733), dedicating it to the latter's son and successor, [[Frederick August II]], in a letter dated 27&nbsp;July 1733. At the time, Bach was in his tenth year as [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] church musician in [[Leipzig]], while the [[Catholic]] court of the sovereign [[Electors of Saxony#Saxony-Poland|Elector of Saxony]] was located in [[Dresden]]. Bach sent performance parts of his {{lang|la|Missa}} to Dresden while he kept the [[autograph score]] in Leipzig. Upon arrival in Dresden, the Mass was not added to the repertoire of the Catholic [[court chapel]], but instead the parts, and Bach's dedication letter, were archived in the sovereign's library.\n\nThe composition, also known as Bach's '''Mass for the Dresden court''', is an unusually extended work scored for five-part [[SATB|SSATB]] soloists and choir with an orchestra having a broad [[Wind instrument|winds section]]. After reusing some of its music in a cantata he composed around 1745 ([[BWV 191]]), Bach finally [[Mass in B minor structure|incorporated the 1733 ''Missa'' as the first of four parts]] of his [[Mass in B&nbsp;minor]], composed/assembled in the last years of his life, around 1748\u20131749. It seems unlikely that the 1733 Kyrie\u2013Gloria Mass, either in its original form or as part of the Mass in B&nbsp;minor, was ever performed during Bach's lifetime.\n\nThe Kyrie\u2013Gloria Mass was not assigned a separate number in the [[Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis|BWV catalogue]], but in order to distinguish it from the later complete mass ({{nowrap|[[BWV 232]]}}), numbers like '''{{nowrap|BWV 232a}}''' and {{nowrap|'''BWV 232<sup>I</sup>'''}} are in use.<ref name=\"Laurson\" />{{sfn|Stockigt|2013}} In 2005 [[B\u00e4renreiter]] published the Mass in the [[New Bach Edition]] series as '''{{lang|de|Missa, {{nowrap|BWV 232 I,}} Fassung von 1733}}''' (i.e. 1733 version of [[Missa, BWV&nbsp;232&nbsp;I]]), in a volume of early versions of the Mass in B&nbsp;minor.<ref name=\"B\u00e4renreiter\" /> That volume also contained early versions of the Credo (BWV 232 II) and Sanctus (BWV 232 III) of the later Mass.<ref name=\"B\u00e4renreiter\" /> Bach's Mass for the Dresden court is also referred to as '''''{{nowrap|Missa 1733}}'''''<ref name=\"Grob\" /> and \"The {{lang|la|Missa}} of 1733\".<ref name=\"Butt\" /> The [[Bach Digital]] website refers to the work as \"BWV 232/I (Fr\u00fchfassung)\", i.e. early version of [[Mass in B minor#I. Kyrie and Gloria (\"Missa\")|Part I of BWV&nbsp;232]].<ref name=\"BDW0290\">Bach Digital Work {{BDW|0290}} at {{url|www.bach-digital.de}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{See also|Bach's church music in Latin}}\nBach was a [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] church musician, devoted to the composition of sacred music in German. He wrote more than 200 [[Church cantata (Bach)|cantatas for the liturgy]], most of them in [[Leipzig]] from 1723 to 1726 at the beginning of his tenure as ''[[Thomaskantor]]'', responsible for the music at the major churches. In Leipzig, a university city where Latin was understood, musical settings of the traditional Latin texts were performed on festive holidays. Bach composed [[Bach's church music in Latin|works on Latin texts]], for example a [[Magnificat in E-flat major, BWV 243a|Magnificat]] in 1723, performed both on the Marian feast [[Visitation (Christianity)|Visitation]] and Christmas that year, and in 1724 a [[Sanctus]] for Christmas, which he later integrated into his [[Mass in B minor structure#Sanctus|Mass in B minor]].<ref name=\"Butt\" /><ref name=\"Steinitz\" /> Both works were exceptional settings: the Magnificat extended to five vocal parts and the Sanctus to six voices, when four-part singing was common in Leipzig.<ref name=\"Rathey\" />\n\n=== Bach's intentions with the composition ===\n[[Augustus the Strong]], [[List of Polish monarchs#Elective Kings of Poland (Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth)|King of Poland]] and [[Electorate of Saxony|Elector of Saxony]], died on 1 February 1733. He had converted to the [[Catholic Church]] in order to ascend to the throne of Poland in 1697. During a period of mourning, no cantata performances were permitted in Leipzig, interrupting Bach's normal work of a weekly cantata performance. Bach was free to compose a Kyrie\u2013Gloria Mass for the court of Dresden,<ref name=\"Leipzig\" /><ref name=\"Leisinger\" /> where the successor was the later [[Augustus III of Poland]]. Bach presented the parts of the works to him with a note dated 27 July 1733, in the hope of obtaining the title \"Saxon Electoral Court Composer\":\n{{quote|In deepest Devotion I present to your Royal Highness this small product of that science which I have attained in Musique, with the most humble request that you will deign to regard it not according to the imperfection of its Composition, but with a most gracious eye&nbsp;... and thus take me into your most mighty Protection.<ref name=\"Talbeck\" />}}\nA different translation of this polite understatement{{sfn|Wolff|2013|p=11}} is \"an insignificant product of the skill I have attained in music.\"<ref name=\"WDL\" /> In the note, Bach also complained that he had \"innocently suffered one injury or another\" in [[Leipzig]].<ref>An English translation of the letter is given in Hans T. David and Arthur Mendel, ''The Bach Reader: A Life of Johann Sebastian Bach in Letters and Documents'', W. W. Norton & Company, 1945, p. 128. (Also in \"The New Bach Reader: A Life of Johann Sebastian Bach in Letters and Documents\" revised by [[Christoph Wolff]], W. W. Norton & Co Inc, 1998, {{ISBN|978-0-393-04558-1}} , p. 158.)</ref> Petitions to the new ruler after the death of the previous one, as the one sent by Bach, were not exceptional in nature: similar petitions by musicians to August III included those of [[Jan Dismas Zelenka]] (unsuccessfully competing with [[Johann Adolph Hasse]] for the post of [[Kapellmeister]]),<ref name=\"Zelenka-Hasse\">[http://www.earlymusicworld.com/id16.html Dresden in the time of Zelenka and Hasse] at {{url|earlymusicworld.com}}, quoted from ''Goldberg Early Music Magazine''.</ref> [[Johann Joachim Quantz]] and [[Pantaleon Hebenstreit]] (a Lutheran court church director).{{sfn|Stockigt|2013|p= 40}} What was exceptional was that Bach accompanied his petition with a composition of considerable dimensions \u2014 a liturgical composition, no less \u2014 which was surprising in that Bach was then employed as a Lutheran church composer and was here presenting a work for the Catholic liturgy.\n[[File:LageEhemaligesOpernhausAmTaschenberg1828.jpg|thumb|500px|This detail from an 1828 map of Dresden shows the location of the [[Opernhaus am Taschenberg]], the court theatre that in the 1660s was built adjacent to the Elector's palace, then in 1708 transformed into the Catholic Hofkirche, and, by the time this map was drawn, after building the [[Hofkirche (Dresden)|Katholische Kirche]] (1739\u20131751), among others, transformed into an archive (indicated as \"'''Archiv'''\" in the middle of this picture).<ref>\"Musical chronicle of the city of Dresden.\" in Medien-Info by Dresden Marketing GmbH, 2013</ref><br />The location of the [[Sophienkirche, Dresden|Sophienkirche]] is shown in the lower part of this detail.]]\nAt the time, Germany lived under the ''[[cuius regio, eius religio]]'' principle (inhabitants of a region have to follow the religion of their ruler), which led to a somewhat double situation in Dresden under August the Strong: officially Catholic in Poland but only privately so in Dresden \u2014 no Catholicism was imposed on Lutheran Saxony, and only the court at Dresden was Catholic.{{sfn|Leaver|2013|pp=25-27}} Lutherans, including the [[Electress#Electresses of Saxony|Electress]] [[Christiane Eberhardine of Brandenburg-Bayreuth|Christiane Eberhardine]], who steadfastly refused to convert to Catholicism (and for whom Bach had composed his ''[[Trauer-Ode|Trauerode]]'' when she died in 1727),<ref name=\"Zelenka-Hasse\" /> had the [[Sophienkirche, Dresden|Sophienkirche]] as their place of worship,{{efn|Note that the Sophienkirche was not called the Hofkirche before 1737, so for the purposes of this article about a 1733 composition, \"Hofkirche\" refers exclusively to the ''Catholic'' court church housed in the former [[Opernhaus am Taschenberg]] and served by the court chapel musicians (also predating plans for the later [[Hofkirche (Dresden)|Hofkirche/Cathedral]] built between the later [[Schlo\u00dfplatz (Dresden)|Schlo\u00dfplatz]] and Theaterplatz within about half a decade).}} while the Catholic Hofkirche (Court church) was housed in the former [[Opernhaus am Taschenberg|court theatre]] from 1708.{{sfn|Leaver|2013|p=27}}\n\nLuther had not rejected any of the [[Mass (music)|five parts of the Mass ordinary that traditionally were eligible for a musical setting]] (Kyrie, Gloria, [[Nicene Creed]], Sanctus, {{nowrap|Agnus Dei}}): Protestant mass celebrations could include any of these and/or their translation in the local language.{{sfn|Leaver|2013|pp=24-25}} There is no doubt that Bach admired his ancestor [[Veit Bach|Veit]] for his Lutheranism.{{sfn|Leaver|2013|pp=}} In all probability Bach wrote a Lutheran liturgical composition that would have been just as acceptable in a Catholic mass. At least the panache with which Bach showed off as a versatile composer, only six years after openly choosing the Lutheran side at the death of the new elector's mother, must be admired.\n\nFor the music, Bach borrowed extensively from his previous cantata compositions.{{sfn|Wolff|2013|p=11}} Bach may have had the capabilities of the singers and instrumentalists of the Dresden [[court chapel]] (which served the Hofkirche) in mind when composing the piece: at the time these included [[Johann Georg Pisendel]] (violinist and [[concert master]]), Johann Christian Richter (oboist), and the flautists [[Pierre-Gabriel Buffardin]] and Johann Joachim Quantz.{{sfn|Stockigt|2013|pp=46-47}} These performers, versed in the French as well as Italian performance styles, were the best of what could be found anywhere in Europe.<ref name=\"Zelenka-Hasse\" /> The new elector's taste for the operatic genre was no secret either.<ref name=\"Zelenka-Hasse\" /> For church music the [[Neapolitan mass]] came closest to that genre, and this was the preferred Mass type at the Hofkirche.{{sfn|Stockigt|2013}} Bach was no doubt aware that apart from the excellent instrumentalists, the Dresden Hofkapelle (\"court chapel\") also had vocal soloists at its disposal (such as [[Faustina Bordoni]], the wife of [[Johann Adolph Hasse]]) who could excel in the type of arias that was customary in operas and Neapolitan masses.{{sfn|Stockigt|2013}}<ref name=\"Zelenka-Hasse\" />\n\nThe score Bach sent to Dresden consisted of the separate parts for [[Soprano]] I, Soprano II, [[Alto]], [[Tenor]], [[Bass (voice type)|Bass]], [[Trumpet]] I, Trumpet II, Trumpet III, [[Timpani]], [[Corno da caccia|Corno da Caccia]], [[Flauto traverso]] I, Flauto traverso II, [[Oboe]] ([[Oboe d'amore|d'amore]]) I, Oboe (d'amore) II, Oboe (d'amore) III, [[Violin]]s I (2 copies), Violins II, [[Viola]], [[Cello]], [[Bassoon]] and [[Basso continuo]]. Most of these copies were written by Bach himself, but for the last movements of both Kyrie and Gloria his sons [[Carl Philipp Emanuel Bach|Carl Philipp Emanuel]] (soprano parts), [[Wilhelm Friedemann Bach|Wilhelm Friedemann]] (violino I parts), and his wife [[Anna Magdalena Bach|Anna Magdalena]] (cello parts) helped, along with an anonymous copyist (oboe and basso continuo parts).<ref>[http://www.bach-digital.de/receive/BachDigitalSource_source_00002721 D-Dl Mus.2405-D-21] at Dresden, S\u00e4chsische Landesbibliothek \u2013 Staats- und Universit\u00e4tsbibliothek (University library), available online at {{url|bach-digital.de}}</ref> Performance material for the choir was not included, nor was the basso continuo part very elaborated.{{sfn|Stockigt|2013|p=53}} All these parts appear to have been copied directly from the full score, which Bach kept in Leipzig.<ref name=\"Butt\" /> Bach supplied the parts for single performers with many details that are not in the score he kept.<ref name=\"Leisinger Interview\" />\n[[File:Dresden Inneres der Hofkapelle 1719.jpg|thumb|500px|Interior of the Hofkirche (Hofkapelle){{efn|Court chapel: in this instance referring to the church building; other instances of Hofkapelle/court chapel in this article generally refer to [[chapel (music)|chapel as an ensemble of musicians]], directed by a [[chapel master]] (Kapellmeister).}} in 1719<ref>Hubert Ermisch. ''[[:File:Ermisch Das alte Archivgeb\u00e4ude am Taschenberge in Dresden.pdf|Das alte Archivgeb\u00e4ude am Taschenberge in Dresden: Ein Erinnerungsblatt]]''. Dresden: Baensch, 1888.</ref>]]\nAlthough some commentators suggest other liturgical and worldly venues where Bach may have anticipated a performance of the {{lang|la|Missa}},{{sfn|Stockigt|2013|p=41}} there seems little doubt that Bach intended to tailor the piece so that it could be performed at the Dresden Hofkirche.{{sfn|Stockigt|2013}}\n\n=== Reception at the Dresden court ===\nWhen the composition arrived in Dresden its format wasn't very unusual compared to other works performed at the time at the Hofkirche. The repertoire performed there included over thirty masses consisting of only a Kyrie and Gloria. Many of these were composed or acquired by the court composer at the time [[Jan Dismas Zelenka]]; and in most cases, as also happened with Bach's {{lang|la|Missa}}, these were later expanded into a complete mass ([[missa tota]]), or at least a Mass with all the usual Mass sections except the Credo ([[missa senza credo]]). Nor the fact that Bach's {{lang|la|Missa}} was composed for virtuoso performers, nor that it was a composition requiring a [[SATB|SSATB]] choir could be considered exceptional at the time and place.{{sfn|Stockigt|2013}}\n\nThe [[key signature]] of the mass was somewhat exceptional: the Hofkirche 1765 catalogue<ref>Janice B. Stockigt. \"\u201cCATALOGO (THEMATICO) [SIC] DELLA MUSICA DI CHIESA (CATHOLICA [SIC] IN DRESDA) COMPOSTA DA DIVERSI AUTORI \u2013 SECONDO L\u2019ALFABETTO '''1765'''\u201d: AN INTRODUCTION\"</ref> contains only one Missa in B minor, by [[Antonio Caldara]]. [[D major]], the relative major key of B minor (i.e. with the same accidentals), was the most usual key for festive music including trumpets, because of the Saxon [[natural trumpet]]: all of Zelenka's solemn masses were in that key, but also 6 of the 12 movements of Bach's {{lang|la|Missa}} (including the Christe eleison and the opening and closing movements of the Gloria) have that same key signature. The most exceptional feature of Bach's mass appears to have been its duration, which largely exceeded what was usual compared to similar compositions at the time in Dresden. This seems the most likely reason why the composition was filed in the Royal Library upon arrival in Dresden, instead of being added to the repertoire of the Hofkirche.{{sfn|Stockigt|2013}}\n\nAs for the result of his petition to the new ruler in Dresden: some three years after his request Bach received the title of Royal Court Composer.{{sfn|Stockigt|2013}} In the intermediate period the Elector had other business to attend to: the [[War of the Polish Succession#Poland|War of the Polish Succession]].\n\n=== Performance history before being integrated in the Mass in B minor, BWV 232 ===\n[[File:Dresden Sophienkirche Lithographie.jpg|thumb|[[Sophienkirche, Dresden]], possibly the location of a first performance]]\nIt is debated if the {{lang|la|Missa}} was performed at the time.<ref name=\"Butt\" /> If it was performed, the most likely venue was the Sophienkirche in Dresden, where Bach's son [[Wilhelm Friedemann Bach|Wilhelm Friedemann]] had been organist since June.<ref name=\"Butt\" /><ref>The details added in this section are from Christoph Wolff \"Bach\", III, 7 (\u00a7&nbsp;8), ''[[Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians|Grove Music Online]]'' ed., L. Macy. http://www.grovemusic.com/ . Last accessed August 9, 2007.</ref>\n\nAround 1745 Bach used three movements of the [[Gloria in excelsis Deo|Gloria]] of the {{lang|la|Missa}} of 1733 for his cantata [[Gloria in excelsis Deo, BWV 191|''Gloria in excelsis Deo'', BWV 191]].<ref name=\"Butt\" /><ref name=\"Steinitz\" />\n\n== Scoring and structure \u2014 incorporation in the Mass in B minor, BWV 232 ==\n{{Main|Mass in B minor structure}}\n\nIn the last years of his life, presumably around 1748\u20131749, Bach integrated the complete {{lang|la|Missa}} of 1733 unchanged in his [[Mass in B minor]], his only missa tota.<ref name=\"Laurson\" /> Scoring and structure are identical with the later work, but markings differ because the parts contain more details than the 1733 score which he kept. Bach made changes{{vague|date=November 2014}} to that score when he completed the mass.<ref name=\"Leisinger Interview\" />\n\nThe work is scored for five vocal parts, two [[soprano]]s, [[alto]], [[tenor]] and [[Bass (voice type)|bass]], and an [[Baroque instruments|orchestra]] of three trumpets, timpani, corno da caccia, two flauti traversi, two oboes, two oboes d'amore, two bassoons, two violins, viola, and basso continuo.\n\nThe [[Mass in B minor structure#Parts and movements|Kyrie]] is structured in three movements. Two different choral movements frame a duet for two sopranos. The [[Mass in B minor structure#Gloria|Gloria]] is structured in nine movements in a symmetric arrangement around a duet of soprano and tenor.\n\nThe {{lang|la|Missa}} of 1733 forms a considerable part of the Mass in B minor which publisher [[Hans Georg N\u00e4geli]] described in 1818 as \"the greatest musical art work of all times and nations\" when he tried a first publication.<ref name=\"WDL\" />\n\n== Publication ==\n\nIn 2005, [[B\u00e4renreiter]] published the work, titled \"Missa, BWV 232 I, Fassung von 1733\", as part of the [[Neue Bach Ausgabe]]. The editor of three ''Early Versions of the Mass BWV 232'', the others being \"Credo in unum Deum, BWV 232 II, Fr\u00fchfassung in G\" and \"Sanctus, BWV 232 III, Fassung von 1724\" was [[Uwe Wolf (musicologist)|Uwe Wolf]].<ref name=\"B\u00e4renreiter\" />\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist\n| colwidth = 30em\n| refs =\n\n<ref name=\"Leipzig\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.bach-digital.de/receive/BachDigitalWork_work_00000290?lang=en\n| title = Missa b-minor (Kyrie and Gloria of the b-minor Mass)) BWV 232 (Fr\u00fchfassung); BC E 2 / Mass\n| publisher = [[University of Leipzig]]\n| accessdate = 28 October 2014\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Butt\">{{cite book\n| last = Butt\n| first = John\n| authorlink = John Butt (musician)\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=rMZqTYkm0DwC&pg=PA9\n| title = Bach: Mass in B Minor\n| year = 1991\n| publisher = [[Cambridge University Press]]\n| isbn = 0-521-38716-7\n| pages = 8\u201312\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Grob\">{{cite web\n| last = Grob\n| first = Jochen\n| url = http://www.s-line.de/homepages/bachdiskographie/vok_lat/vok_lat_messen.html\n| title = Missa 1733\n| publisher = s-line.de\n| language = German\n| accessdate = 28 October 2014\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140819181912/http://www.s-line.de/homepages/bachdiskographie/vok_lat/vok_lat_messen.html\n| archive-date = 19 August 2014\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Laurson\">{{cite web\n| last = Laurson\n| first = Jens F.\n| url = http://www.musicweb-international.com/classrev/2009/Aug09/Bach_Missa_2564690571.htm\n| title = Johann Sebastian Bach (1685\u20131750) / Missa (1733)\n| publisher = musicweb-international.com\n| year = 2009\n| accessdate = 12 February 2013\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Leisinger\">{{cite book\n| last = Leisinger\n| first = Ulrich\n| url = http://www.carus-verlag.com/images-intern/pdf/Artikel/3123200-foreword.pdf\n| title = Foreword\n| year = 2014\n| publisher = [[Carus-Verlag]]\n| format = PDF\n| pages = IV\u2013VI\n| access-date = 2014-12-06\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141209105532/http://www.carus-verlag.com/images-intern/pdf/Artikel/3123200-foreword.pdf\n| archive-date = 2014-12-09\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Leisinger Interview\">{{cite book\n| last = Leisinger\n| first = Ulrich\n| url = http://www.carus-verlag.com/carus-magazin-01-2014-bach-h-moll-messe.en.html\n| title = \"Care is an editor's highest priority\"\n| year = 2014\n| publisher = [[Carus-Verlag]]\n| pages = IV\u2013VI\n| language = German\n| access-date = 2014-10-29\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141029114812/http://www.carus-verlag.com/carus-magazin-01-2014-bach-h-moll-messe.en.html\n| archive-date = 2014-10-29\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Rathey\">{{cite web\n| last = Rathey\n| first = Markus\n| url = http://bach.nau.edu/mass/prose/Rathey.pdf\n| title = Johann Sebastian Bach's Mass in B Minor: The Greatest Artwork of All Times and All People\n| publisher = bach.nau.edu\n| format = PDF\n| year = 2003\n| accessdate = 17 September 2013\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131005014030/http://bach.nau.edu/mass/prose/Rathey.pdf\n| archive-date = 5 October 2013\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref>\n<!-- not needed but kept here because it's mentioned on the talk\n<ref name=\"Smith\">{{cite web\n| last = Smith\n| first = Tim\n| url = http://bach.nau.edu/mass/prose/assembly.pdf\n| publisher = bach.nau.edu\n| title = Assembly of the Mass\n| format = PDF\n| accessdate = 29 October 2014\n}}</ref> -->\n\n<ref name=\"Steinitz\">{{cite web\n| last = Steinitz\n| first = Margaret\n| url = http://www.aucx96.dsl.pipex.com/Lbsdb/LBSDB_LC_INTRO.html\n| title = Bach's Latin Church Music\n| accessdate = 16 September 2010\n| publisher = [[London Bach Society]]\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110715085014/http://www.aucx96.dsl.pipex.com/Lbsdb/LBSDB_LC_INTRO.html\n| archive-date = 15 July 2011\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Talbeck\">{{cite web\n| last = Talbeck\n| first = Carol\n| url = http://www.sfchoral.org/site/bach-b-minor-mass/\n| title = Johann Sebastian Bach: Mass in B Minor / Everything must be possible. \u2013 J. S. Bach.\n| publisher = sfchoral.org\n| year = 2002\n| accessdate = 13 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"WDL\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.wdl.org/en/item/11619/\n| title = Missa in B Minor (\"Kyrie\" and \"Gloria\" of the B Minor Mass)\n| website = [[World Digital Library]]\n| accessdate = 8 August 2013\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"B\u00e4renreiter\">{{cite web\n| url = https://www.baerenreiter.com/en/search/product/?artNo=BA5293-01\n| title = Missa, BWV 232 I, Fassung von 1733, in \"Bach, Johann Sebastian / Early Versions of the Mass BWV 232\"\n| year = 2005\n| website = [[B\u00e4renreiter]]\n| accessdate = 3 November 2014\n}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== Sources ==\n\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|editor-last1=Tomita|editor-first1=Yo |editor-last2=Leaver|editor-first2=Robin A. |editor-last3=Smaczny|editor-first3=Jan |title=Exploring Bach's B-minor Mass|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZbT1AAAAQBAJ|date= 2013|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-00790-1|pp=3\u201320|first=Christoph |last=Wolff|chapter=Past, present and future perspectives on Bach's B-minor Mass}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|editor-last1=Tomita|editor-first1=Yo |editor-last2=Leaver|editor-first2=Robin A. |editor-last3=Smaczny|editor-first3=Jan |last=Leaver|first=Robin A. |title=Exploring Bach's B-minor Mass|url=https://books.google.com